            "content": "# Native Rendering Override Architecture\n\n> Supersedes: the blanket CSS `!important` override path in `applyOverride`.\n> References: [2026-02-25-visual-editor-standalone-product.md](./2026-02-25-visual-editor-standalone-product.md) (IC1 finding), [2026-02-25-visual-editor-implementation.md](./2026-02-25-visual-editor-implementation.md) (Phase 4 override engine), [2026-02-18-visual-editing-session-loop-and-token-toolbar.md](./2026-02-18-visual-editing-session-loop-and-token-toolbar.md) (`detectStyleOrigin` design)\n> Companion issues: ZF0-859 (token enforcement), ZF0-857 (inspector bug fixes — in progress, parallel work)\n\n---\n\n## 1. Problem Statement\n\nThe current override engine applies every CSS change through a single path:\n\n```\napplyOverride(selId, prop, value)\n  → overrideRules[selector][prop] = value\n  → updateOverrideSheet()\n  → <style> tag with `!important` declarations\n```\n\nThis creates a **fidelity gap** between preview and committed code:\n\n| Scenario | Preview renders via | Committed code renders via |\n|----------|-------------------|---------------------------|\n| Mantine `p=\"md\"` → `p=\"lg\"` | `padding: 40px !important` (pixel value) | `var(--mantine-spacing-lg)` (CSS variable) |\n| Tailwind `p-4` → `p-8` | `padding: 32px !important` (pixel value) | `p-8` class (Tailwind utility) |\n\nThe pixel values may coincidentally match, but the rendering path is different. CSS variable cascading, Tailwind's responsive prefixes, and theme switching can all cause the committed result to diverge from the preview.\n\n`detectStyleOrigin` (in `scripts/visual-toolbar.js:68`) already classifies every CSS value by its source framework. The override engine ignores this information.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Design Principles\n\n1. **Native path when possible** — Override using the same mechanism the framework uses. The preview should be indistinguishable from the committed result.\n2. **Graceful degradation** — When native override isn't feasible, fall back to CSS `!important` and flag the preview as approximate.\n3. **Reconciliation-safe** — Overrides must survive React re-renders and HMR. (IC1 finding: inline `element.style` changes get wiped by React reconciliation.)\n4. **Clean reversal** — Every override strategy must have a complete undo path that leaves zero DOM artifacts.\n5. **Minimal surface** — Don't introduce new frameworks or abstraction layers. Extend existing patterns (`messageHandlers` dispatch table, `overrideRules` storage).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Current Architecture (Status Quo)\n\n### Functions (in `inspector.js` on `main`)\n\n| Function | Lines | Role |\n|----------|-------|------|\n| `buildOverrideCSS(rules)` | 252-268 | Serializes rules → CSS text with `!important` |\n| `parseOverrideRules(css)` | 270-296 | Deserializes CSS text → rules (strips `!important`) |\n| `buildSelector(selId)` | 537-556 | Resolves `selId` → CSS selector (`data-testid` > `data-cortex-id` > auto-generated) |\n| `applyOverride(selId, prop, value)` | 574-583 | Validates + stores rule + flushes sheet |\n| `removeOverride(selId, prop)` | 585-595 | Deletes rule + flushes sheet |\n| `updateOverrideSheet()` | 558-572 | Syncs `overrideRules` → `<style id=\"__zerofog_overrides__\">` |\n\n### Storage Model\n\n```\noverrideRules: {\n  '[data-testid=\"card\"]': { padding: '16px', gap: '8px' },\n  '[data-cortex-id=\"zerofog-3\"]': { margin: '24px' }\n}\n```\n\nFlat `{ selector: { prop: value } }` dictionary. No metadata about how the override was applied.\n\n### `detectStyleOrigin` Return Types (in `toolbar.d.ts`)\n\n```typescript\ntype StyleOrigin =\n  | { origin: 'mantine-prop'; prop: string; value: unknown; component: string }\n  | { origin: 'mantine-default'; component: string; defaultValue: unknown }\n  | { origin: 'tailwind'; className: string }\n  | { origin: 'css-module' }\n  | { origin: 'unknown' };\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Proposed Architecture: Strategy Dispatch\n\n### 4.1 Overview\n\n`applyOverride` gains an `origin` parameter and dispatches to a strategy handler:\n\n```\nPanel calls detectStyleOrigin(element, property)\n  → origin: { origin: 'mantine-prop', prop: 'p', value: 'md', component: 'Card' }\n\nPanel sends zerofog:preview message with origin attached\n  → applyOverride(selId, 'padding', 'var(--mantine-spacing-lg)', origin)\n    → dispatch to mantineStrategy.apply(...)\n```\n\n### 4.2 Strategy Registry\n\n```javascript\nvar overrideStrategies = Object.create(null);\noverrideStrategies['mantine-prop']    = mantineStrategy;\noverrideStrategies['mantine-default'] = mantineStrategy;\noverrideStrategies['tailwind']        = tailwindStrategy;\noverrideStrategies['css-module']      = cssImportantStrategy;\noverrideStrategies['unknown']         = cssImportantStrategy;\n```\n\nEach strategy implements:\n\n```typescript\ninterface OverrideStrategy {\n  apply(element: Element, selId: number, cssProperty: string, cssValue: string, origin: StyleOrigin): OverrideRecord;\n  remove(element: Element, record: OverrideRecord): void;\n}\n```\n\n### 4.3 Dispatch Flow\n\n```javascript\nfunction applyOverride(selId, cssProperty, cssValue, origin) {\n  if (!selId) return;\n  if (ALLOWED_CSS_PROPERTIES.indexOf(cssProperty) === -1) return;\n  if (CSS_VALUE_UNSAFE.test(cssValue)) return;\n\n  var el = elementMap[selId];\n  if (!el) return;\n\n  var originType = (origin && origin.origin) || 'unknown';\n  var strategy = overrideStrategies[originType] || cssImportantStrategy;\n\n  // Remove existing override for this property (if any) before applying new one\n  var existingKey = selId + ':' + cssProperty;\n  if (overrideRecords[existingKey]) {\n    var oldRecord = overrideRecords[existingKey];\n    var oldStrategy = overrideStrategies[oldRecord.originType] || cssImportantStrategy;\n    oldStrategy.remove(el, oldRecord);\n  }\n\n  var record = strategy.apply(el, selId, cssProperty, cssValue, origin);\n  overrideRecords[existingKey] = record;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Override Strategies\n\n### 5a. Mantine Strategy (`mantine-prop`, `mantine-default`)\n\n**Goal:** Override renders identically to what changing the Mantine prop in source would produce.\n\n**Approach:** CSS `<style>` tag with Mantine CSS variable references (not pixel values).\n\n**Why not inline styles?** IC1 finding (standalone product doc): `element.style.setProperty` overrides are wiped by React reconciliation. Every re-render would destroy the preview. The `<style>` tag approach survives because React doesn't touch injected `<style>` elements.\n\n**Why CSS variables?** A Mantine `<Card p=\"lg\">` ultimately renders as `padding: var(--mantine-spacing-lg)`. By using the CSS variable in our override, we match the exact cascade that production Mantine uses. Theme switches, responsive overrides, and dark mode all work because the variable resolves through Mantine's CSS variable layer.\n\n**Apply:**\n\n```javascript\nvar mantineStrategy = {\n  apply: function (el, selId, cssProperty, cssValue, origin) {\n    // cssValue should already be a CSS variable reference: 'var(--mantine-spacing-lg)'\n    // The panel resolves token → CSS variable before sending the message.\n    var selector = buildSelector(selId);\n    if (!selector) return null;\n\n    // Store in overrideRules for the CSS sheet path\n    if (!overrideRules[selector]) overrideRules[selector] = Object.create(null);\n    overrideRules[selector][cssProperty] = cssValue;\n    updateOverrideSheet();\n\n    return {\n      strategy: 'mantine-var',\n      originType: origin.origin,\n      selId: selId,\n      selector: selector,\n      cssProperty: cssProperty,\n      cssValue: cssValue,\n      component: origin.component || null,\n      prop: origin.prop || null\n    };\n  },\n\n  remove: function (el, record) {\n    var rules = overrideRules[record.selector];\n    if (rules) {\n      delete rules[record.cssProperty];\n      if (Object.keys(rules).length === 0) delete overrideRules[record.selector];\n    }\n    updateOverrideSheet();\n  }\n};\n```\n\n**Rendering comparison:**\n\n| Aspect | Current (`!important`) | Proposed (CSS variable) |\n|--------|----------------------|------------------------|\n| Value in `<style>` tag | `padding: 40px !important` | `padding: var(--mantine-spacing-lg) !important` |\n| Theme switch | Stale pixel value | Updates automatically |\n| Dark mode | Stale pixel value | Updates automatically |\n| Matches committed code | Only if pixel value matches | Yes — same CSS variable |\n\n**Note:** `!important` is still used for specificity (the Mantine component's own styles may have specificity from CSS-in-JS or CSS modules). The difference is the *value* is now native — the variable reference, not a resolved pixel value. This is a pragmatic compromise: native value, robust delivery mechanism.\n\n### 5b. Tailwind Strategy (`tailwind`)\n\n**Goal:** Override renders identically to what changing the Tailwind class in source would produce.\n\n**Approach:** Swap class tokens on the element's `classList`. Use a MutationObserver to re-apply the swap after React reconciliation.\n\n**Why class swapping?** Tailwind utilities are atomic CSS classes. The only way to get identical rendering is to use the actual class. A CSS `!important` override with a pixel value won't pick up Tailwind's responsive breakpoints, dark mode variants, or JIT-generated utilities.\n\n**Why MutationObserver?** React reconciliation replaces `className` on re-render, wiping our class swap. A MutationObserver on the element's `class` attribute detects this and re-applies the swap. This is a targeted observer (single element, single attribute) — minimal performance cost.\n\n**Apply:**\n\n```javascript\nvar tailwindStrategy = {\n  apply: function (el, selId, cssProperty, cssValue, origin) {\n    // origin.className is the matched Tailwind class (e.g., 'p-4')\n    // cssValue is the new Tailwind class (e.g., 'p-8')\n    // Panel resolves token → Tailwind class before sending.\n    var oldClass = origin.className;\n    var newClass = cssValue;\n\n    // Perform the swap\n    if (oldClass && el.classList.contains(oldClass)) {\n      el.classList.remove(oldClass);\n    }\n    el.classList.add(newClass);\n\n    // Set up MutationObserver for reconciliation survival\n    var observer = new MutationObserver(function (mutations) {\n      for (var i = 0; i < mutations.length; i++) {\n        if (mutations[i].attributeName === 'class') {\n          // React re-rendered — re-apply the swap\n          if (oldClass && el.classList.contains(oldClass)) {\n            el.classList.remove(oldClass);\n          }\n          if (!el.classList.contains(newClass)) {\n            el.classList.add(newClass);\n          }\n        }\n      }\n    });\n    observer.observe(el, { attributes: true, attributeFilter: ['class'] });\n\n    return {\n      strategy: 'tailwind-class',\n      originType: 'tailwind',\n      selId: selId,\n      cssProperty: cssProperty,\n      oldClass: oldClass,\n      newClass: newClass,\n      observer: observer\n    };\n  },\n\n  remove: function (el, record) {\n    // Disconnect observer first to prevent re-application\n    if (record.observer) record.observer.disconnect();\n\n    // Reverse the swap\n    if (record.newClass && el.classList.contains(record.newClass)) {\n      el.classList.remove(record.newClass);\n    }\n    if (record.oldClass) {\n      el.classList.add(record.oldClass);\n    }\n  }\n};\n```\n\n**Reconciliation behavior:**\n\n```\n1. User selects element with class \"p-4\"\n2. applyOverride swaps to \"p-8\", starts MutationObserver\n3. React re-renders component (state change, HMR, etc.)\n4. React sets className back to include \"p-4\"\n5. MutationObserver fires, removes \"p-4\", adds \"p-8\"\n6. Element renders with Tailwind \"p-8\" utility\n```\n\n**Performance note:** One MutationObserver per overridden Tailwind element. With the 50-element cap on `elementMap`, this is bounded at 50 observers maximum. Each observes a single attribute on a single element — negligible overhead.\n\n### 5c. CSS `!important` Fallback (`css-module`, `unknown`)\n\n**Goal:** Provide a functional preview for cases where native rendering isn't feasible.\n\n**Approach:** Existing `<style>` tag with `!important` — unchanged from current implementation.\n\n**Approximate preview flag:** The panel should display a visual indicator when an override uses this fallback:\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────┐\n│ Padding: lg                 │\n│ ⚠ Approximate preview       │\n│   (CSS module — may differ  │\n│    slightly from committed) │\n└─────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**Apply / Remove:** Identical to current `applyOverride` / `removeOverride` logic — store in `overrideRules`, flush via `updateOverrideSheet()`.\n\n```javascript\nvar cssImportantStrategy = {\n  apply: function (el, selId, cssProperty, cssValue, origin) {\n    var selector = buildSelector(selId);\n    if (!selector) return null;\n\n    if (!overrideRules[selector]) overrideRules[selector] = Object.create(null);\n    overrideRules[selector][cssProperty] = cssValue;\n    updateOverrideSheet();\n\n    return {\n      strategy: 'css-important',\n      originType: origin ? origin.origin : 'unknown',\n      selId: selId,\n      selector: selector,\n      cssProperty: cssProperty,\n      cssValue: cssValue,\n      approximate: true\n    };\n  },\n\n  remove: function (el, record) {\n    var rules = overrideRules[record.selector];\n    if (rules) {\n      delete rules[record.cssProperty];\n      if (Object.keys(rules).length === 0) delete overrideRules[record.selector];\n    }\n    updateOverrideSheet();\n  }\n};\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Storage Model\n\n### 6.1 New: `overrideRecords`\n\nReplace the implicit storage in `overrideRules` (CSS-only) with explicit per-override metadata:\n\n```javascript\n// Keyed by \"selId:cssProperty\" — one record per property per element\nvar overrideRecords = Object.create(null);\n```\n\nEach record contains enough information to reverse the override:\n\n```typescript\ntype OverrideRecord =\n  | {\n      strategy: 'mantine-var';\n      originType: 'mantine-prop' | 'mantine-default';\n      selId: number;\n      selector: string;\n      cssProperty: string;\n      cssValue: string;         // e.g., 'var(--mantine-spacing-lg)'\n      component: string | null;\n      prop: string | null;      // e.g., 'p' (the Mantine prop name)\n    }\n  | {\n      strategy: 'tailwind-class';\n      originType: 'tailwind';\n      selId: number;\n      cssProperty: string;\n      oldClass: string;         // e.g., 'p-4' (class that was removed)\n      newClass: string;         // e.g., 'p-8' (class that was added)\n      observer: MutationObserver;\n    }\n  | {\n      strategy: 'css-important';\n      originType: 'css-module' | 'unknown';\n      selId: number;\n      selector: string;\n      cssProperty: string;\n      cssValue: string;\n      approximate: true;\n    };\n```\n\n### 6.2 Retained: `overrideRules`\n\n`overrideRules` is retained as-is for the Mantine and CSS-fallback strategies (both use the `<style>` tag). It remains the serialization source for `buildOverrideCSS`. Tailwind overrides are NOT stored in `overrideRules` — they operate directly on the DOM.\n\n### 6.3 Cleanup on Deactivate\n\nThe `deactivate()` function must iterate `overrideRecords` and call each strategy's `remove()`:\n\n```javascript\n// In deactivate():\nvar recordKeys = Object.keys(overrideRecords);\nfor (var i = 0; i < recordKeys.length; i++) {\n  var record = overrideRecords[recordKeys[i]];\n  var el = elementMap[record.selId];\n  var strategy = overrideStrategies[record.originType] || cssImportantStrategy;\n  if (el) strategy.remove(el, record);\n  delete overrideRecords[recordKeys[i]];\n}\n// Also clear overrideRules and remove <style> tag (existing logic)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Message Protocol Changes\n\n### 7.1 `zerofog:preview` Payload\n\nCurrent:\n```javascript\n{ selectionId: number, cssProperty: string, cssValue: string }\n```\n\nProposed:\n```javascript\n{\n  selectionId: number,\n  cssProperty: string,\n  cssValue: string,     // Strategy-appropriate value (CSS var, Tailwind class, or pixel)\n  origin: StyleOrigin   // From detectStyleOrigin — tells inspector which strategy to use\n}\n```\n\n### 7.2 `zerofog:revert` Payload\n\nUnchanged:\n```javascript\n{ selectionId: number, cssProperty: string }\n```\n\nThe inspector looks up the `overrideRecords` entry to determine which strategy's `remove()` to call. No origin needed for reversal.\n\n### 7.3 Panel Responsibility: Value Resolution\n\nThe panel (not the inspector) is responsible for resolving the user's token selection into the correct `cssValue` format:\n\n| Origin | User selects token \"lg\" | Panel sends `cssValue` |\n|--------|------------------------|----------------------|\n| `mantine-prop` | lg | `var(--mantine-spacing-lg)` |\n| `mantine-default` | lg | `var(--mantine-spacing-lg)` |\n| `tailwind` | lg → maps to Tailwind scale | `p-8` (the Tailwind class) |\n| `css-module` | lg | `40px` (resolved pixel value) |\n| `unknown` | lg | `40px` (resolved pixel value) |\n\nThis keeps the inspector's dispatch logic simple — it receives a ready-to-apply value and just routes to the right strategy.\n\n---\n\n## 8. React Reconciliation Analysis\n\n### 8.1 The IC1 Problem\n\nFrom the standalone product doc: React re-renders replace DOM attributes (including `style` and `className`) with values from the virtual DOM. Any direct DOM mutation gets wiped.\n\n### 8.2 Survival Matrix\n\n| Strategy | Mechanism | Survives reconciliation? | How |\n|----------|-----------|-------------------------|-----|\n| Mantine (CSS var) | `<style>` tag | Yes | React doesn't touch injected `<style>` elements |\n| Tailwind (class swap) | `classList` + MutationObserver | Yes | Observer re-applies swap after React resets classes |\n| CSS fallback | `<style>` tag | Yes | Same as Mantine |\n\n### 8.3 HMR Behavior\n\nHot Module Replacement replaces the entire component tree. After HMR:\n\n- **`<style>` tag overrides** (Mantine, CSS fallback): Survive. The style tag is outside React's tree.\n- **Tailwind class swaps**: The element may be destroyed and recreated. The MutationObserver is attached to the old element. After HMR, the override is lost.\n\n**Mitigation for Tailwind + HMR:** On `zerofog:selected` (re-selection after HMR), the panel re-sends all active overrides for the selected element. This is already part of the planned Phase 4b re-selection flow. The three-phase commit (existing design) handles the override clearing after source edits are verified.\n\n### 8.4 Element Unmounting\n\nIf a Tailwind-overridden element gets unmounted (SPA navigation, conditional rendering):\n\n1. MutationObserver becomes inert (observing a detached node — no cost)\n2. `overrideRecords` still holds the record\n3. On `deactivate()` or next override of same `selId:prop`, the record is cleaned up\n4. The disconnected observer is garbage-collected with the detached element\n\nNo memory leak because `elementMap` already has a 50-element cap with eviction.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Edge Cases\n\n### 9.1 Multiple Overrides on Same Element, Different Strategies\n\nPossible scenario: element has both a Mantine prop (`p=\"md\"`) and a Tailwind class (`rounded-lg`). User overrides both.\n\n- Padding override → `mantineStrategy` (stored in `overrideRecords` as `selId:padding`)\n- Border-radius override → `tailwindStrategy` (stored as `selId:border-radius`)\n\nNo conflict — each record is independent, keyed by `selId:cssProperty`.\n\n### 9.2 Responsive Tailwind Variants\n\nIf an element has `p-4 md:p-8`, `detectStyleOrigin` matches `p-4` (the first match). Swapping `p-4` → `p-6` doesn't affect `md:p-8`. At `md` breakpoint, the responsive variant still applies.\n\n**Limitation:** The editor cannot currently preview responsive overrides (e.g., \"change `md:p-8` to `md:p-12`\"). This is out of scope for v1 — document as a known limitation. The panel should not offer responsive variant editing.\n\n### 9.3 Tailwind Dark Mode / State Variants\n\nIf the element has `p-4 dark:p-6`, the swap targets `p-4` only. In dark mode, `dark:p-6` takes precedence via Tailwind's specificity cascade. The preview correctly reflects this — the swap only affects the base variant.\n\n### 9.4 Origin Detection Failure\n\nIf `detectStyleOrigin` returns `{ origin: 'unknown' }` for a value that is actually Mantine or Tailwind, the fallback strategy (CSS `!important`) activates. The preview is approximate but functional.\n\n**Future improvement:** origin detection accuracy can be improved independently. The strategy dispatch model is correct regardless — better detection → better fidelity, no architecture changes needed.\n\n### 9.5 Mixed Mantine + Tailwind App\n\nSome apps use both frameworks. `detectStyleOrigin` has a priority cascade: Mantine props > Mantine theme defaults > Tailwind classes > CSS modules > unknown. This is the correct precedence because Mantine props are the most specific signal (directly on the component fiber).\n\n---\n\n## 10. Compatibility with ZF0-859 (Token Enforcement)\n\nZF0-859 adds token validation to `applyOverride` — rejecting values that don't map to known design tokens. The dispatch model is compatible:\n\n1. Token validation runs first (before strategy dispatch)\n2. If the value fails validation, `applyOverride` returns early (no strategy invoked)\n3. Strategy handlers receive already-validated values\n\nThe validation check should occur against the *resolved* value, not the CSS variable. For Mantine: `var(--mantine-spacing-lg)` should be validated by extracting the token name (`lg`) and checking it against the token map.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit Tests (pure functions, no DOM)\n\n- `applyOverride` dispatches to correct strategy based on origin type\n- `removeOverride` calls correct strategy's `remove()` method\n- `overrideRecords` stores/retrieves/deletes correctly\n- Strategy registry returns `cssImportantStrategy` for unknown origin types\n\n### IIFE Integration Tests (happy-dom)\n\nPer the issue's automated verification criteria:\n\n- [ ] Mantine origin override: `<style>` tag contains CSS variable reference (not pixel value)\n- [ ] Tailwind origin override: element's `classList` contains new class, not old class\n- [ ] CSS module origin: falls back to CSS `!important` with pixel value\n- [ ] `removeOverride` reverses each strategy cleanly (no DOM artifacts)\n- [ ] Tailwind override survives simulated React reconciliation (class attribute reset)\n- [ ] MutationObserver is disconnected on `removeOverride`\n- [ ] `deactivate()` cleans up all override types (records, observers, style tag)\n- [ ] Multiple override types on same element coexist correctly\n\n### Manual Verification\n\nPer the issue's criteria:\n\n- [ ] Override a Mantine `p=\"md\"` element — DevTools shows CSS variable in `<style>` tag, not pixel value\n- [ ] Override renders identically to what changing the prop in source would produce\n- [ ] Override a Tailwind `p-4` element — DevTools shows class changed to new utility\n- [ ] Theme switch (dark mode) with active Mantine override — value updates automatically\n\n---\n\n## 12. Implementation Sequence\n\nThis spec is implemented in Phase 4b alongside the panel UI:\n\n1. **Add `overrideRecords` storage** alongside existing `overrideRules`\n2. **Implement `cssImportantStrategy`** — extract existing logic into strategy object (no behavior change)\n3. **Implement `mantineStrategy`** — CSS variable path through `<style>` tag\n4. **Implement `tailwindStrategy`** — class swap + MutationObserver\n5. **Add strategy registry** (`overrideStrategies` dispatch table)\n6. **Modify `applyOverride`** — accept `origin` parameter, dispatch to strategy\n7. **Modify `removeOverride`** — look up record, call strategy's `remove()`\n8. **Modify `deactivate()`** — iterate records, call each strategy's `remove()`\n9. **Update message protocol** — `zerofog:preview` payload includes `origin`\n10. **Update panel** — resolve tokens to strategy-appropriate `cssValue` format\n11. **Add approximate preview flag** — panel shows indicator for CSS-fallback overrides\n\nSteps 1-2 are a safe refactor (extract existing behavior). Steps 3-4 add new strategies. Steps 5-8 wire the dispatch. Steps 9-11 are panel integration.\n\n---\n\n## 13. Open Questions\n\n1. **Should `buildOverrideCSS` distinguish Mantine overrides visually?** E.g., a comment in the generated CSS: `/* mantine-var */ padding: var(--mantine-spacing-lg) !important`. Useful for debugging but adds complexity to the serializer.\n\n2. **Should `finalizeDiff` include strategy metadata?** When the user hits \"Finalize,\" the diff JSON currently contains `{ property, oldValue, newValue }`. Adding `{ strategy, origin }` would help Claude's Code Translator generate the correct source edit (change Mantine prop vs. swap Tailwind class). This is likely required — spec for ZF0-860 (finalize pipeline) should address this.\n\n3. **Tailwind JIT: are all utility classes pre-generated?** If the target Tailwind class (`p-8`) wasn't in the original build, it may not exist in the stylesheet. Tailwind JIT generates classes on demand at build time, not runtime. If the class doesn't exist, the swap has no effect. Mitigation: for Tailwind apps using JIT, we may need a fallback to CSS `!important` with the computed value. Detection: check if the swapped class actually applies styles via `getComputedStyle` after the swap.\n",
