ops, specific component breakdown) because they had codebase access.\n\n**C2. Finalize Pipeline Needs a Spec (9/10 reviewers)**\n\n`finalizeDiff()` produces JSON. Nothing consumes it. The PM (clink) and PM (native) both independently recommended adding a \"Phase 6a\" or inserting a spec into Phase 4b planning:\n\n- Minimum: diff JSON → Claude prompt → copy-to-clipboard (validates the concept)\n- Target: diff JSON → Claude prompt → proposed source edit → developer approval UI\n- Stretch: Streaming preview while Claude generates\n\n*New finding from native reviews:* The frontend (native) reviewer identified that `parseOverrideRules` in inspector.js uses a regex that breaks on nested `@media` blocks — this would affect the finalize pipeline's ability to read back current overrides.\n\n### HIGH — Should fix in v1\n\n**H1. Token Enforcement at Engine Level (5/10)**\n\n`applyOverride` accepts any CSS value. Token validation must happen in the engine, not just the UI. Add `reverseTokenLookup` validation for spacing/radius properties.\n\n*Phase assignment:* **4b** — implement alongside panel UI.\n\n**H2. Preview Fidelity Gap (7/10)**\n\nThe highest-flagged non-critical finding. `!important` CSS overrides produce different rendering than Mantine props or Tailwind classes due to specificity, inheritance, and cascade differences.\n\n*Short-term (4b):* Add a confidence indicator — \"High fidelity\" for color/font changes, \"Approximate\" for spacing (where cascade matters).\n*Long-term (v1.5):* Apply overrides via Mantine theme modification at runtime instead of CSS injection.\n\n**H3. Define MLP Before Building More (4/10)**\n\nCDO (clink) and 3 native reviewers flagged: the project is building a platform without defining the minimum lovable product. What's the smallest thing a design engineer can do end-to-end that makes them come back tomorrow?\n\n*Proposed MLP:* Select element → see current tokens → change spacing → see live preview → copy diff JSON. That's it. No Claude integration, no source editing, no undo history. If this loop doesn't feel magical, nothing else matters.\n\n**H4. `elementMap` DOM Reference Leak (3/10 — new finding from native)**\n\nThe frontend (native) reviewer found that `elementMap` (inspector.js line 342) stores direct DOM element references that are never cleaned up on SPA navigation. When React unmounts and remounts components, the map holds stale references to detached DOM nodes — a memory leak that grows with every route change.\n\n*Fix:* Clear `elementMap` on `deactivate()` and on `popstate`/`pushState` events. Use WeakRef if targeting modern browsers.\n\n**H5. Non-Unique testId Collision (3/10 — new finding from native)**\n\n`buildSelector` assumes `data-testid` is unique per page. If two elements share a testId (common with list items: `data-testid=\"list-item\"`), overrides bleed across elements.\n\n*Fix:* When multiple elements match a testId selector, fall back to `data-cortex-id` with auto-assignment.\n\n**H6. Override State Lost on Reactivation (3/10 — new finding from native)**\n\n`deactivate()` (inspector.js line 612) wipes `overrideRules`, destroying all accumulated overrides. If the user toggles inspect mode off and back on, their work is gone.\n\n*Fix:* Preserve `overrideRules` across deactivate/activate cycles. Only clear on explicit \"Discard All.\"\n\n### MEDIUM\n\n- **Mantine lock-in** — Extract `DesignSystemAdapter` interface. Mantine first, then Tailwind/Chakra/Radix. Target: v1.1.\n- **SPA navigation** — Already planned in Phase 5. Move critical path (override persistence) to Phase 4b.\n- **Zero-to-feedback loop** — No onboarding, no empty states, no guided first interaction. Add to Phase 4b.\n- **320px panel width** — Too narrow for token editing with per-side controls. Make resizable or widen to 380px.\n- **`buildTokenMaps` causes layout thrash** — Sentinel element forces style recalculation. Use `requestAnimationFrame` or batch reads.\n- **CLI entry point is a stub** — `bin.ts` exists but isn't connected. Phase 6 addresses this.\n- **Missing sandbox permissions** — `shell.html` iframe needs `allow-downloads` and `allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation`.\n- **Fiber adapter** — All `__reactFiber$` access should be behind an adapter with graceful degradation. Target: v1.1.\n\n### LOW\n\n- No keyboard shortcuts for common operations\n- No batch element selection\n- No visual diff indicator for pending overrides\n- No component variant awareness (Mantine filled/outline/subtle)\n- CLI command name too long — consider shorter alias\n- No formatted error messages from sidecar\n\n---\n\n## Positive Practices — Preserve These\n\nCarried forward from UX review, reinforced by all 10 reviewers:\n\n1. **Strong security posture** — CSS injection validation, postMessage origin checking, sessionId verification. Native frontend reviewer confirmed the F4 fix is production-grade.\n2. **181 tests with excellent edge case coverage** — React 18/19 paths, malformed inputs, DOM cleanup. Native reviewers praised test quality.\n3. **Clean separation of concerns** — Pure functions in toolbar.js, IIFE isolation at runtime, ESM for testing. This pattern enables the chat UI pivot without rewriting.\n4. **Forward-compatible React fiber traversal** — Dual-strategy pattern acknowledged by all technical reviewers as best available approach for an inherently unstable dependency.\n5. **Idempotent injection** — Critical for HMR workflows. Native DX reviewer confirmed this prevents the most common developer frustration (double-injected scripts after hot reload).\n6. **Batch editing model** — \"Accumulate then commit\" is the right UX for design iteration. This naturally extends to the chat UI where Claude proposes multiple changes before applying.\n7. **Token-constrained philosophy** — The *intention* is correct. Enforcement needs to catch up (H1), but the design decision is sound.\n8. **Well-sequenced implementation plan** — PM (clink): \"7 of 9 findings are already addressed by the plan structure.\" The bottom-up build order (infrastructure → scripts → integration) produces testable artifacts at each phase.\n\n---\n\n## New Bugs Found by Native Reviewers\n\nThe native agents, with direct codebase access, identified implementation bugs not visible to clink reviewers:\n\n| Bug | File | Line(s) | Severity | Discoverer |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| `elementMap` never clears DOM refs — memory leak on SPA navigation | inspector.js | 342, 462-468 | HIGH | frontend (native) |\n| `parseOverrideRules` regex breaks on nested `@media` blocks | inspector.js | 276 | HIGH | frontend (native) |\n| Non-unique `data-testid` causes override bleed across elements | inspector.js | 539-556 | HIGH | frontend (native) |\n| `deactivate()` wipes override state — toggles destroy user work | inspector.js | 612-644 | HIGH | frontend (native) |\n| `buildTokenMaps` sentinel causes synchronous layout thrash | toolbar.js | 39-42 | MEDIUM | frontend (native) |\n| Missing `allow-downloads`, `allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation` in iframe sandbox | shell.html | 28 | MEDIUM | dx (native) |\n\n---\n\n## Methodology Comparison: Clink vs Native\n\n### What Clink Uniquely Caught\n- **Strategic product positioning** — PM (claude-clink) produced the sharpest analysis: \"7 of 9 findings already planned.\" No native reviewer caught this explicitly.\n- **Competitive landscape** — PM (claude-clink) mapped the competitive field (Vercel v0, bolt.new, Cursor) and differentiated Cortex's position.\n- **CDO vision framing** — CDO (codex-clink) coined \"building the wrong product first\" — the visual editor is training wheels, chat UI is the bicycle. Strategic insight not seen in native reviews.\n- **Design system extraction as \"10x wedge\"** — CDO (codex-clink) identified bottom-up token discovery as the competitive differentiator vs. Figma's top-down approach.\n- **MLP definition gap** — CDO (codex-clink) flagged \"building platform not product\" — need to define the minimum lovable expe