          "text": "\n\n## Task 1: Fix 4 HIGH Inspector Bugs\n\nThese are all in `inspector.js` — defects found by native reviewers with codebase access.\n\n**Bug 1 — `elementMap` DOM reference leak (line 342)**\n\n`elementMap` stores direct references to DOM elements keyed by `selectionId`. When the user navigates to a different route in a SPA (React Router), React unmounts those components and creates new DOM nodes. But `elementMap` still holds references to the old, detached nodes. The garbage collector can't free them because `elementMap` keeps them reachable.\n\nResult: memory grows with every route change. After navigating through 20 pages, you have 20 pages worth of dead DOM nodes in memory.\n\nFix: Clear `elementMap` entries when elements are no longer in the document. Either clear on route change events (`popstate`/`pushState`) or use `WeakRef` so the GC can collect detached nodes naturally.\n\n**Bug 2 — `parseOverrideRules` regex breaks on nested `@media` (line 276)**\n\n`buildOverrideCSS` / `parseOverrideRules` uses a regex to parse CSS rules from the `<style id=\"__zerofog_overrides__\">` tag. The regex assumes flat rules — `selector { property: value; }`. If someone introduces `@media` queries (which the responsive/breakpoint work would need), the regex breaks because it sees the nested `}` and splits rules incorrectly.\n\nThis isn't causing bugs today (no `@media` in overrides yet), but it blocks future work and is fragile. The fix is to either use a proper CSS parser or handle nesting depth in the regex.\n\n**Bug 3 — Non-unique `data-testid` collision (lines 539-556)**\n\n`buildSelector` looks for `data-testid` on an element and builds a selector like `[data-testid=\"card\"]`. But if the page has a list of cards, every card has `data-testid=\"card\"`. The override targets ALL of them — user changes padding on one card, all cards change.\n\nFix: Before using a `data-testid` selector, check if `document.querySelectorAll('[data-testid=\"card\"]').length > 1`. If so, fall back to the auto-assigned `data-cortex-id` which is unique per selection.\n\n**Bug 4 — `deactivate()` wipes override state (lines 612-644)**\n\nWhen the user toggles inspect mode off (or the panel sends a deactivate message), `deactivate()` clears `overrideRules`. When they toggle back on, all their accumulated edits are gone.\n\nThis is the worst one from a UX perspective. The user spends 10 minutes tweaking spacing across 5 components, accidentally toggles mode, and loses everything.\n\nFix: `deactivate()` should tear down event listeners and overlays but preserve `overrideRules` and the override stylesheet. Only clear on explicit \"Discard All\" from the panel.\n\n---\n\n## Task 2: Fix 2 MEDIUM Bugs\n\n**Bug 5 — `buildTokenMaps` sentinel causes layout thrash (toolbar.js lines 39-42)**\n\n`buildTokenMaps` creates a hidden `<div>`, appends it to `document.body`, sets CSS variables as styles, then reads back computed values. Each `getComputedStyle()` call after a style change forces the browser to synchronously recalculate layout. The function does this in a loop for every token size (5 iterations for spacing + 5 for radius = 10 forced layouts).\n\nFix: Batch all style writes first, then batch all reads. Or use `requestAnimationFrame` to defer reads to the next frame.\n\n**Bug 6 — Missing iframe sandbox permissions (shell.html line 28)**\n\nThe iframe sandbox attribute is missing `allow-downloads` and `allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation`. If the proxied app has download links or needs to navigate the top frame (e.g., OAuth redirects), they silently fail.\n\nFix: Add the two missing permissions to the `sandbox` attribute.\n\n---\n\n## Task 3: Token Enforcement in `applyOverride`\n\nThis is the gap between philosophy and implementation. The product says \"token-constrained editing — only design system values.\" But `applyOverride` accepts any CSS property and any value. The F4 security fix added an allowlist for properties and a character blocklist for values (no `{};<>`), but that's injection safety, not token enforcement.\n\nRight now, if the panel sends `applyOverride(selId, 'padding', '47px')`, the engine happily applies it. 47px isn't a design token. The override engine should reject values that don't map to known tokens.\n\nFix: For spacing and radius properties, run the value through `reverseTokenLookup`. If the value doesn't map to a known token (xs/sm/md/lg/xl), reject it. Color and font properties have different validation rules (color must be a CSS variable or hex from the theme, font-size/weight must match the type scale).\n\nThis is separate from the bugs because it changes the `applyOverride` contract — it goes from \"accepts anything safe\" to \"accepts only token-valid values.\" That's a feature change, not a defect fix.\n\n---\n\n## Task 4: Write Finalize Pipeline Spec\n\nThis is the one 9 out of 10 reviewers flagged as CRITICAL. `finalizeDiff()` in toolbar.js produces a JSON object:\n\n```js\n{\n  elementSelector: '[data-testid=\"hero\"]',\n  componentChain: ['HeroSection', 'Box'],\n  elementType: 'div',\n  changes: [...],\n  timestamp: '2026-02-28T...'\n}\n```\n\nNothing consumes this. There's no spec for what happens next. Phase 6 mentions \"integration test covering sidecar-to-browser-to-source flow\" but doesn't spec the Claude integration.\n\nThe task is to write an architecture spec answering:\n- What prompt does Claude receive? (diff JSON + source file contents? just diff?)\n- How does the system identify which source file to modify? (`componentChain` → file lookup?)\n- What's the approval flow? (Claude proposes edit → shown in panel → user approves → applied to disk?)\n- What's the minimum viable version? (copy diff JSON to clipboard for paste into Claude Code?)\n- How does this interact with the native rendering approach from task 5? (if overrides use real Mantine tokens, the diff JSON already contains token names, not raw px values)\n\nThis is a document, not code. But it unblock