            "content": "# Linear Issue ID: [TO BE ASSIGNED]\n\n# Post-Strategic-Review: Inspector Bugs + Architecture Specs\n\n**Status**: Ready\n**Priority**: High\n**Assignee**: dlee\n**Estimate**: 15 points\n**Labels**: bug, architecture, frontend\n**Project**: Cortex\n\n## Description\nAddress 6 implementation bugs found by native architecture reviewers and 3 architecture gaps identified by 10-reviewer consensus. Bugs stabilize the inspector and override engine before Phase 4b panel work begins. Architecture specs (finalize pipeline, native rendering, structural editing) define unplanned work that emerged from the strategic review.\n\n## Key Details\n- 4 HIGH bugs in inspector.js found by native reviewers with codebase access\n- 2 MEDIUM bugs in toolbar.js and shell.html\n- Token enforcement gap between \"token-constrained\" philosophy and actual engine behavior\n- Finalize pipeline (9/10 consensus) has zero spec — highest-risk assumption in the product\n- Preview fidelity approach corrected: use native rendering (Mantine vars, Tailwind classes), not CSS `!important` overrides\n- Structural editing architecture needs scoping to prevent 10x scope creep\n\n## Test Strategy\n- Unit tests for each bug fix (targeting ~12 new tests across inspector + toolbar)\n- Token enforcement tests (valid/invalid token values)\n- Architecture specs are documents, not code — reviewed via `/architecture-review`\n\n## Implementation Notes\nTasks 1-3 should land before Phase 4b begins (they stabilize the foundation). Task 4 (finalize spec) unblocks Phase 6 design. Task 5 (native rendering) changes how Phase 4b's panel applies overrides. Task 6 (structural editing) is v1.5/v2 planning.\n\n## Dependencies\n- Depends on: Phase 4a (ZF0-848) — complete\n- Blocks: Phase 4b (ZF0-849) — bugs must be fixed, native rendering architecture must be designed before panel sends overrides\n\n## References\n- Strategic review: `tasks/phase4a-strategic-review.md`\n- UX review: `tasks/phase4a-ux-review.md`\n- Implementation plan: `tasks/implement-visual-editor.md`\n- Inspector source: `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js`\n- Toolbar source: `visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`\n\n---\n\n# Sub-Tasks\n\n## 1. Fix 4 HIGH inspector bugs\n**Linear ID**: [TO BE ASSIGNED]\n**Priority**: High\n**Estimate**: 3 points\n**Status**: Ready\n**Dependencies**: None\n\n### Description\nFix 4 implementation defects in `inspector.js` discovered by native architecture reviewers. These bugs cause memory leaks, override bleed across elements, state loss on mode toggle, and a regex that blocks future responsive override support.\n\n### Implementation Steps\n\n#### Bug A — `elementMap` DOM reference leak (line 342)\n1. `elementMap` stores direct DOM references keyed by `selectionId`\n2. On SPA navigation, React unmounts components but `elementMap` keeps stale references to detached nodes\n3. Fix: Add cleanup on route change events. Listen for `popstate` and monkey-patched `pushState`/`replaceState` to clear entries whose elements are no longer in the document (`!document.contains(el)`)\n4. Alternative: Use a wrapper that checks `document.contains(el)` before returning from `elementMap` lookups, and lazily prunes stale entries\n\n#### Bug B — `parseOverrideRules` regex breaks on nested blocks (line 276)\n1. `rulePattern = /([^{]+)\\{([^}]*)\\}/g` assumes flat CSS rules\n2. Any `@media` or `@supports` block with nested `{}` causes incorrect rule splitting\n3. Fix: Replace regex with a brace-depth-aware parser that tracks nesting level. Only split at depth 0. The format is machine-generated (by `buildOverrideCSS`), so the parser can be simple — it just needs to handle one level of nesting for `@media` blocks\n\n#### Bug C — Non-unique `data-testid` collision (lines 539-556)\n1. `buildSelector` uses `[data-testid=\"card\"]` without checking if multiple elements share that testId\n2. Override bleeds to all matching elements when user only selected one\n3. Fix: Before using testId as selector, check `document.querySelectorAll('[data-testid=\"' + testId + '\"]').length`. If >1, auto-assign `data-cortex-id` and use that instead\n4. Note: Users may intentionally want to edit all elements with the same testId (batch editing). The rule is: the selector must scope to exactly the elements the user selected. Single selection → unique selector. Future batch selection → one override per selected element\n\n#### Bug D — `deactivate()` wipes override state (lines 612-649)\n1. `deactivate()` clears both `overrideRules` (line 626-629) and removes the override stylesheet (line 624-625)\n2. `activate()` calls `deactivate()` first (line 649) for idempotent re-attachment\n3. Result: toggling inspect mode destroys all accumulated edits\n4. Fix: Split `deactivate()` into two concerns:\n   - `teardownListeners()` — removes event listeners, hides overlays, clears hover state\n   - `discardOverrides()` — clears `overrideRules`, removes stylesheet (only called on explicit \"Discard All\")\n   - `deactivate()` calls `teardownListeners()` only. `activate()` calls `teardownListeners()` then re-attaches\n   - `elementMap` clearing moves to a separate `clearStaleElements()` called on route change, not on deactivate\n\n### Success Criteria\n\n#### Automated Verification\n- [ ] `npm test` — all existing + new tests pass\n- [ ] Test: `elementMap` entries for detached DOM nodes are pruned after simulated navigation\n- [ ] Test: `parseOverrideRules` correctly parses CSS with one level of `@media` nesting\n- [ ] Test: `buildSelector` returns unique `data-cortex-id` selector when `data-testid` is shared by multiple elements\n- [ ] Test: `buildSelector` uses `data-testid` when it is unique on the page\n- [ ] Test: overrides survive `deactivate()` → `activate()` cycle\n- [ ] Test: overrides are cleared only on explicit `discardOverrides()` call\n\n#### Manual Verification\n- [ ] Navigate between routes — no memory growth in DevTools heap snapshot\n- [ ] Select one card in a list — only that card's spacing changes\n- [ ] Toggle inspect mode off and on — overrides still visible\n\n### Code References\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:342` — `elementMap` declaration\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:276` — `parseOverrideRules` regex\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:539-556` — `buildSelector`\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:612-649` — `deactivate()` and `activate()`\n- `visual-editor/tests/client/inspector.test.ts` — add tests\n\n---\n\n## 2. Fix 2 MEDIUM bugs (layout thrash + sandbox permissions)\n**Linear ID**: [TO BE ASSIGNED]\n**Priority**: Medium\n**Estimate**: 1 point\n**Status**: Ready\n**Dependencies**: None\n\n### Description\nFix two medium-severity issues: `buildTokenMaps` causing synchronous layout thrash, and missing iframe sandbox permissions in `shell.html`.\n\n### Implementation Steps\n\n#### Bug E — `buildTokenMaps` sentinel causes layout thrash (toolbar.js lines 39-57)\n1. The loop sets a style property (`sentinel.style.padding = ...`), then immediately reads computed style (`_getStyle(sentinel).paddingTop`). Each read after a write forces synchronous layout recalculation\n2. This happens 10 times (5 spacing sizes + 5 radius sizes)\n3. Fix: Batch writes and reads. Create 10 sentinel elements (or reuse one with 10 different class toggles), set all styles first, then read all computed values. Or use `requestAnimationFrame` to defer reads to after the browser's next layout pass\n4. Simpler alternative: Since this runs once on init, the perf impact is ~10ms. If we keep the current approach, add a comment explaining the tradeoff. Only refactor if profiling shows measurable impact\n\n#### Bug F — Missing iframe sandbox permissions (shell.html line 28)\n1. Current sandbox: `allow-same-origin allow-scripts allow-forms allow-modals allow-popups allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox`\n2. Missing: `allow-downloads` (download links in proxied app silently fail) and `allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation` (OAuth redirects fail)\n3. Fix: Add both permissions to the `sandbox` attribute\n\n### Success Criteria\n\n#### Automated Verification\n- [ ] `npm test` — all tests pass\n- [ ] Test: `buildTokenMaps` produces correct maps (existing tests still pass)\n- [ ] `npm run typecheck` — no type errors\n\n#### Manual Verification\n- [ ] Shell iframe loads proxied app without sandbox errors in console\n- [ ] Download links in proxied app work\n- [ ] No visible jank during `buildTokenMaps` initialization\n\n### Code References\n- `visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js:39-57` — `buildTokenMaps` loop\n- `visual-editor/src/client/shell.html:28` — iframe sandbox attribute\n\n---\n\n## 3. Add token enforcement in `applyOverride`\n**Linear ID**: [TO BE ASSIGNED]\n**Priority**: High\n**Estimate**: 2 points\n**Status**: Ready\n**Dependencies**: #1\n\n### Description\nClose the gap between the \"token-constrained editing\" philosophy and the override engine's actual behavior. Currently `applyOverride` accepts any CSS value that passes injection-safety checks. It should additionally reject values that don't map to known design system tokens for spacing and radius properties.\n\n### Implementation Steps\n1. In `applyOverride` (inspector.js line 574), after the existing `ALLOWED_CSS_PROPERTIES` and `CSS_VALUE_UNSAFE` checks, add token validation for spacing/radius properties\n2. Define which properties require token validation:\n   - Spacing: `padding`, `padding-*`, `margin`, `margin-*`, `gap`, `row-gap`, `column-gap`\n   - Radius: `border-radius`, `border-*-radius`\n3. For these properties, the value must be either:\n   - A CSS variable reference: `var(--mantine-spacing-md)` (native rendering path)\n   - A known token name: `md`, `lg`, `xl` (panel shorthand that gets resolved)\n   - A value that `reverseTokenLookup` maps to a token\n4. Properties NOT requiring token validation: `color`, `background-color`, `font-size`, `font-weight`, `font-family`, `display` — these have different constraint models\n5. Expose token validation as a testable function: `isTokenValue(property, value, tokenMaps)`\n6. The panel UI (Phase 4b) will only send token values, but the engine enforces the constraint independently — defense in depth\n\n### Success Criteria\n\n#### Automated Verification\n- [ ] Test: `applyOverride` accepts `var(--mantine-spacing-md)` for padding\n- [ ] Test: `applyOverride` accepts `md` for padding (token name shorthand)\n- [ ] Test: `applyOverride` rejects `47px` for padding (not a token)\n- [ ] Test: `applyOverride` accepts arbitrary values for `color` and `font-size` (no token constraint)\n- [ ] Test: `isTokenValue` correctly validates against token maps\n- [ ] All existing override tests still pass\n\n#### Manual Verification\n- [ ] Console: `applyOverride(1, 'padding', '47px')` silently rejected (no override created)\n- [ ] Console: `applyOverride(1, 'padding', 'var(--mantine-spacing-md)')` applies correctly\n\n### Code References\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:574-583` — `applyOverride`\n- `visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js:74-83` — `reverseTokenLookup`\n- `visual-editor/tests/client/inspector.test.ts` — add tests\n\n---\n\n## 4. Write finalize pipeline spec\n**Linear ID**: [TO BE ASSIGNED]\n**Priority**: Urgent\n**Estimate**: 3 points\n**Status**: Ready\n**Dependencies**: None\n\n### Description\nWrite the architecture spec for the finalize pipeline — the flow from diff JSON to source code changes. This was flagged by 9/10 reviewers as the highest-risk assumption in the product. `finalizeDiff()` produces JSON but nothing consumes it. Phase 6 mentions integration testing but doesn't spec the Claude integration. This document unblocks Phase 6 implementation design.\n\n### Implementation Steps\n1. Create `thoughts/shared/plans/2026-03-XX-finalize-pipeline-spec.md`\n2. The spec must answer:\n\n**Input format:**\n- Is the current `finalizeDiff()` output sufficient? It produces `{ elementSelector, componentChain, changes, timestamp }`\n- Does it need the source file path? How is that determined from `componentChain`?\n- With the native rendering approach (task 5), changes will contain token names and CSS variable references, not raw px values — how does this improve the prompt?\n\n**Claude integration:**\n- What prompt does Claude receive? (diff JSON + source file contents? project context?)\n- How does the system identify which source file to modify? (component name → file path mapping? fiber `_debugSource`?)\n- What structured output format does Claude return? (unified diff? line-specific edits?)\n\n**Approval flow:**\n- How does the user review proposed changes? (panel UI? terminal output? both?)\n- What's the rollback mechanism? (git stash? undo stack?)\n\n**MVP definition:**\n- Minimum: diff JSON → copy-to-clipboard for paste into Claude Code\n- Target: diff JSON → Claude prompt → proposed source edit → panel approval → applied to disk\n- What validates the concept at each tier?\n\n**Interaction with other systems:**\n- How does this interact with the sidecar WebSocket? (panel sends diff via WS → sidecar calls Claude?)\n- How does this interact with the state machine (Phase 5)? (`idle → pending_diff → processing`)\n- Selection scope: if user edited one card (unique selector), does Claude change one JSX instance? If user edited all cards, does Claude change the component definition?\n\n3. Review spec via `/architecture-review` before implementation begins\n\n### Success Criteria\n\n#### Automated Verification\n- [ ] N/A — this is a document, not code\n\n#### Manual Verification\n- [ ] Spec answers all questions listed above\n- [ ] Spec reviewed and approved\n- [ ] Phase 6 implementation plan updated to reference this spec\n- [ ] `finalizeDiff()` output format validated as sufficient or change proposed\n\n### Code References\n- `visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js:214-228` — `finalizeDiff()`\n- `visual-editor/src/server.ts` — `POST /diff` endpoint (consumer)\n- `tasks/implement-visual-editor.md` — Phase 6 (ZF0-851)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Design native rendering override architecture\n**Linear ID**: [TO BE ASSIGNED]\n**Priority**: High\n**Estimate**: 3 points\n**Status**: Ready\n**Dependencies**: #1\n\n### Description\nReplace the CSS `!important` override approach with native rendering — apply changes through the same mechanism the framework uses. If the app uses Mantine, edit Mantine's CSS variables. If Tailwind, swap Tailwind classes. The preview should be indistinguishable from the final committed result because it uses the same rendering path.\n\n`detectStyleOrigin` already identifies the source of every CSS value. The override engine should dispatch through the matching channel instead of always injecting CSS.\n\n### Implementation Steps\n1. Create architecture spec: `thoughts/shared/plans/2026-03-XX-native-rendering-overrides.md`\n2. Document the dispatch strategy per origin:\n\n**Mantine prop** (`origin: 'mantine-prop'`):\n- `p=\"md\"` compiles to CSS using `var(--mantine-spacing-md)`\n- Override: set `element.style.padding = 'var(--mantine-spacing-lg)'` (inline style wins specificity over class-based styles)\n- The preview uses the real Mantine CSS variable — renders identically to what `p=\"lg\"` would produce\n- No `!important` needed\n\n**Mantine theme default** (`origin: 'mantine-default'`):\n- Same mechanism as explicit prop — the CSS variable reference is the same\n- Override: same inline style approach\n\n**Tailwind class** (`origin: 'tailwind'`):\n- `p-4` applies padding via Tailwind's utility class\n- Override: remove `p-4` from `element.classList`, add `p-8`\n- The preview uses real Tailwind CSS — renders identically\n- Need to handle responsive prefixes: `sm:p-4` → `sm:p-8`\n\n**CSS module** (`origin: 'css-module'`):\n- Class names are hashed at build time — can't swap classes\n- Fallback: CSS override (the existing `!important` approach) — this is ~3% of the target app\n- Flag in panel as \"approximate preview\"\n\n**Unknown origin:**\n- Fallback: CSS override with `!important`\n- Flag in panel as \"approximate preview\"\n\n3. Modify `applyOverride` to accept origin info and dispatch:\n   ```\n   applyOverride(selId, cssProperty, cssValue, origin)\n   ```\n   - `origin` comes from `detectStyleOrigin` call in the panel before sending the override\n   - Dispatch: Mantine/Tailwind → native path. CSS module/unknown → CSS fallback\n\n4. Define how `removeOverride` reverses each approach:\n   - Mantine: remove inline style (`element.style.removeProperty('padding')`)\n   - Tailwind: restore original class\n   - CSS module: remove CSS rule\n\n5. Review spec, then implement in Phase 4b alongside panel UI\n\n### Success Criteria\n\n#### Automated Verification\n- [ ] Test: Mantine origin override uses inline style with CSS variable reference\n- [ ] Test: Tailwind origin override swaps class tokens\n- [ ] Test: CSS module origin falls back to CSS `!important` override\n- [ ] Test: `removeOverride` correctly reverses each override type\n- [ ] All existing override tests updated for new dispatch behavior\n\n#### Manual Verification\n- [ ] Override a Mantine `p=\"md\"` element — DevTools shows inline style `padding: var(--mantine-spacing-lg)`, NOT a `<style>` rule\n- [ ] Override renders identically to what changing the prop in source would produce\n- [ ] Override a Tailwind `p-4` element — DevTools shows class changed to `p-8`\n\n### Code References\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:574-583` — `applyOverride` (to modify)\n- `visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js:95-208` — `detectStyleOrigin` (origin detection)\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:558-572` — `updateOverrideSheet` (CSS fallback path)\n\n---\n\n## 6. Design intent-based structural editing architecture\n**Linear ID**: [TO BE ASSIGNED]\n**Priority**: Medium\n**Estimate**: 3 points\n**Status**: Ready\n**Dependencies**: #4, #5\n\n### Description\nWrite the architecture spec for intent-based structural editing — how users add, remove, and rearrange components through the visual editor. This is v1.5/v2 scope. The goal is to define the correct approach upfront to prevent 10x scope creep during implementation.\n\nThree modes, each with constrained workflows:\n\n1. **Edit mode** (default) — User describes changes + panel adjustments on selected component. System provides feedback on what's possible within that component's constraints.\n2. **Add mode** — System highlights insertion points on the page where elements can be added (because fiber traversal knows which components accept children). User picks a spot → workflow: adding a button? existing component? new component? new logic?\n3. **Delete mode** — System highlights removable elements. User picks one → confirm → system captures the removal intent.\n\n### Implementation Steps\n1. Create architecture spec: `thoughts/shared/plans/2026-03-XX-structural-editing-architecture.md`\n2. The spec must define:\n\n**Mode system:**\n- How do Edit/Add/Delete modes integrate with the existing Browse/Select mode toggle?\n- What visual affordances distinguish each mode? (different overlay colors? different cursor?)\n- How does mode state flow between panel and inspector via postMessage?\n\n**Add mode — insertion point detection:**\n- Which fiber nodes can accept new children? (check `fiber.type` for container components: Stack, Group, Grid, Flex, Box)\n- How are insertion points visualized? (horizontal/vertical drop zones between existing children?)\n- What's the workflow after picking a spot?\n  - Adding a known component (Button, Text, etc.) → select from component palette → system inserts with default props\n  - Adding a new component → triggers Claude to scaffold a component based on user description\n  - Adding logic → triggers Claude to add conditional rendering\n\n**Delete mode — removal detection:**\n- Which elements are removable? (leaf components and optional containers — not structural wrappers that would break layout)\n- How does the system determine if removal is safe? (fiber tree analysis: does removing this node orphan its siblings?)\n- What's the confirmation UX?\n\n**Intent capture format:**\n- Extend `finalizeDiff` format to include structural intents:\n  ```json\n  { \"type\": \"add\", \"parent\": \"Stack\", \"position\": 2, \"component\": \"Button\", \"props\": { \"variant\": \"filled\" } }\n  { \"type\": \"remove\", \"target\": \"Subtitle\", \"parent\": \"Card\" }\n  { \"type\": \"reorder\", \"parent\": \"Stack\", \"children\": [\"Title\", \"Body\", \"Subtitle\"], \"newOrder\": [0, 2, 1] }\n  ```\n- How does the finalize pipeline (task 4) translate these intents to JSX changes?\n\n**Preview strategy:**\n- For additions: render a placeholder element styled with the component's default tokens\n- For removals: fade out the element (CSS opacity transition) as preview, actual removal on finalize\n- For reordering: use CSS `order` as temporary preview, JSX reorder on finalize\n\n**Scope boundaries:**\n- What is explicitly out of scope for v1.5? (freeform positioning, custom component authoring, state management)\n- What guardrails prevent scope creep? (only container components support Add, only leaf/optional components support Delete)\n\n3. Review spec before any implementation begins\n\n### Success Criteria\n\n#### Automated Verification\n- [ ] N/A — this is a document, not code\n\n#### Manual Verification\n- [ ] Spec defines all three modes with clear workflows\n- [ ] Insertion point detection algorithm is specified with examples\n- [ ] Intent capture format is defined and compatible with `finalizeDiff` output\n- [ ] Scope boundaries are explicit — what's in and what's out\n- [ ] Spec reviewed and approved\n\n### Code References\n- `visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js:50-83` — `walkComponentChain` (fiber hierarchy)\n- `visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js:214-228` — `finalizeDiff` (to extend)\n- `tasks/phase4a-strategic-review.md` — Q2 corrected framing\n",
