visual editor.\n3. `finalizeDiff` produces a broken/malicious selector that could match unintended elements.\n4. When the panel applies CSS overrides using this selector, it affects elements the user did not intend to modify.\n\n**Cross-reference:** `inspector.js` line 751 has the same pattern but correctly uses `escapeAttrValue`:\n```javascript\nvar escaped = escapeAttrValue(testId);\nvar matches = document.querySelectorAll('[data-testid=\"' + escaped + '\"]');\n```\n\n**Fix:** Use the same `escapeAttrValue` function that `inspector.js` already defines. Since these are independent IIFEs, either duplicate the function in toolbar.js or apply escaping:\n```javascript\nfunction escapeAttrValue(val) {\n  return val.replace(/\\\\/g, '\\\\\\\\').replace(/\"/g, '\\\\\"');\n}\n\nvar selector = selection.testId\n  ? '[data-testid=\"' + escapeAttrValue(selection.testId) + '\"]'\n  : ...\n```\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 2: ReDoS in Tailwind Regex Patterns\n\n**Severity: MEDIUM**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 184-190\n\n**Description:**\nThe Tailwind regex patterns contain the sequence `(?:[\\w-]+:)*` for matching responsive/state prefixes (e.g., `sm:hover:focus:`). The `*` quantifier on a repeating character class group creates potential for polynomial-time backtracking on crafted inputs.\n\nSpecifically, the padding regex:\n```\n/(?:^|\\s)(?:[\\w-]+:)*p[xytblr]?-(\\d+(?:\\.5)?|px|auto|\\[\\S+?\\])/\n```\n\nThe vulnerable portion is `(?:[\\w-]+:)*p`. When a className string contains a long sequence of `[\\w-]` characters followed by `p` but no valid continuation, the regex engine must try all possible splits of the `[\\w-]+` group across multiple repetitions of `(?:[\\w-]+:)*`.\n\n**Attack Scenario:**\n1. A malicious page or component sets `className` to a string like `\"aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaap!\"` (30+ word characters followed by `p` and a non-matching trailer).\n2. `detectStyleOrigin` calls `twPatterns[property].test(classes)`.\n3. The regex engine backtracks exponentially across `(?:[\\w-]+:)*` trying to match the `p` anchor.\n\n**Analysis:**\nI need to be precise: the `(?:[\\w-]+:)*` group requires a colon `:` after each repetition. Without colons in the input, the group matches zero times and falls through to `p[xytblr]?-...`. The real danger is an input like `\"a]a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:a:ap-\"` where each `a:` segment can be consumed by the group. However, because `[\\w-]+:` requires at least one `[\\w-]` character followed by a colon, and `p` is also `[\\w]`, the backtracking occurs when the engine tries to decide whether the `p` belongs to a prefix group or the literal `p` anchor.\n\nLet me verify more precisely:\n\nFor input `\"sm:hover:focus:p-4\"`, the regex works fine. For a pathological input like `\"a]\" + \"x:\".repeat(25) + \"p!\"`, the engine tries every possible way to split `x:x:x:...x:p` between the `(?:[\\w-]+:)*` group and the literal `p`, which is O(n) not exponential because the colon anchoring disambiguates. After further analysis, the colon acts as a strong disambiguator, limiting backtracking significantly.\n\n**Revised severity: LOW-MEDIUM.** The colon anchor in `[\\w-]+:` constrains backtracking meaningfully. However, the `\\[\\S+?\\]` capture for arbitrary bracket values uses a lazy quantifier on `\\S` which could have polynomial behavior on strings like `\"p-[aaaaaaa\"` (unterminated bracket with no `]`).\n\n**Fix:** Use possessive quantifiers or atomic groups if the regex engine supports them. Alternatively, add a maximum length check on className before regex matching:\n```javascript\nvar classes = element.className || '';\nif (typeof classes === 'string' && classes.length < 10000) {\n  // ... regex matching\n}\n```\n\nOr replace `\\[\\S+?\\]` with `\\[[^\\]]+\\]` which removes the ambiguity:\n```javascript\npadding: /(?:^|\\s)(?:[\\w-]+:)*p[xytblr]?-(\\d+(?:\\.5)?|px|auto|\\[[^\\]]+\\])/,\n```\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 3: React Fiber Data as Untrusted Input — Component Name Injection\n\n**Severity: MEDIUM**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 131-153\n\n**Description:**\n`detectStyleOrigin` reads `owner.type.displayName || owner.type.name` and uses the resulting `compName` as a key for theme defaults lookup and as a return value. These values come from React fiber internals which are controlled by whatever code is running in the target application.\n\n```javascript\nvar compName = '';\nif (owner.type) {\n  compName = owner.type.displayName || owner.type.name || '';\n}\n// ...\nvar defaults = _themeDefaults[compName];\n```\n\nA malicious component could set `displayName` to `\"__proto__\"`, `\"constructor\"`, or `\"toString\"` to interact with object prototype methods when used as a lookup key in `_themeDefaults`.\n\n**Attack Scenario:**\n1. A malicious component sets `Component.displayName = '__proto__'`.\n2. `detectStyleOrigin` resolves `compName = '__proto__'`.\n3. `_themeDefaults['__proto__']` accesses `Object.prototype` (not `undefined`), which is an object.\n4. `defaults[defaultPropName]` then reads a property off `Object.prototype`.\n5. If someone has polluted `Object.prototype` elsewhere (common attack pattern), this returns a truthy value and the function returns a `mantine-default` origin with attacker-controlled data.\n\n**Mitigating factor:** `_themeDefaults` defaults to `window.__ZEROFOG__.themeDefaults || {}`. The `|| {}` produces a plain object where `{}['__proto__']` returns `Object.prototype` which is truthy and has properties. However, `Object.prototype['radius']` is `undefined`, so the `if (defaults[defaultPropName] !== undefined)` check would fail unless `Object.prototype` has been polluted.\n\n**Fix:** Use `Object.create(null)` for themeDefaults or add a `hasOwnProperty` guard:\n```javascript\nvar defaults = _themeDefaults[compName];\nif (defaults && Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(_themeDefaults, compName)) {\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 4: Missing Input Validation on Public Functions\n\n**Severity: MEDIUM**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 95, 74, 214\n\n**Description:**\nSeveral public functions lack defensive input validation:\n\n**4a. `detectStyleOrigin` with null/undefined element (line 95):**\nIf `element` is `null` or `undefined`, accessing `element.className` at line 182 throws a TypeError. The `findFiberKeysFn` parameter is called without verifying its return type.\n\n**4b. `reverseTokenLookup` with non-object maps (line 74):**\nIf `maps` is null or undefined, `maps.radius` throws. If `pxValue` is not a string, `parseFloat(pxValue)` on a non-string may produce unexpected results.\n\n**4c. `finalizeDiff` with null selection (line 214):**\nIf `selection` is null, `selection.testId` throws.\n\n**4d. `buildTokenMaps` with null document.body (line 42):**\nIf `document.body` is null (possible during SSR hydration edge cases), `document.body.appendChild(sentinel)` throws. The `typeof document === 'undefined'` check at line 26 does not cover this case.\n\n**Attack Scenario:**\nThese are primarily robustness issues rather than exploitable vulnerabilities. However, an unhandled TypeError could crash the visual editor during operation, which is a denial-of-service against the editing workflow.\n\n**Fix:** Add input validation at the top of each public function:\n```javascript\nfunction detectStyleOrigin(element, property, findFiberKeysFn, themeDefaults) {\n  if (!element || typeof element !== 'object') return { origin: 'unknown' };\n  if (typeof property !== 'string') return { origin: 'unknown' };\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 5: CSS Variable Oracle via `buildTokenMaps` Sentinel\n\n**Severity: LOW**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 39-62\n\n**Description:**\n`buildTokenMaps` creates a visible-in-DOM (though visually hidden) `div` element, sets CSS custom property references as inline styles, and reads back computed values. While the sentinel is only alive during function execution, there is a timing window where:\n\n1. The sentinel element exists in the DOM and is accessible to MutationObservers.\n2. The sentinel reveals which CSS custom properties are defined (by checking whether the resolved value is `0px`).\n3. A `getComputedStyle` call on the sentinel leaks the resolved pixel values of all `--mantine-spacing-*` and `--mantine-radius-*` variables.\n\n**Attack Scenario:**\n1. Malicious code in the target app registers a `MutationObserver` on `document.body`.\n2. When `buildTokenMaps` appends the sentinel, the observer fires.\n3. The observer reads `getComputedStyle(sentinel)` to exfiltrate the design token values.\n4. These values reveal the design system configuration (Mantine theme settings).\n\n**Mitigating factors:** The design token values are typically public (they're applied visually to all elements anyway). This is information that's already observable from any element on the page. The risk is theoretical.\n\n**Fix (defense in depth):** Consider reading the CSS custom properties from an existing element (like `document.documentElement`) via `getComputedStyle(document.documentElement).getPropertyValue('--mantine-spacing-md')` rather than creating a sentinel. This eliminates the DOM mutation entirely:\n```javascript\nvar rootStyle = getComputedStyle(document.documentElement);\nvar spacingPx = rootStyle.getPropertyValue('--mantine-spacing-' + s).trim();\n```\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 6: `className` as SVGAnimatedString (Non-String className)\n\n**Severity: LOW**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, line 182-183\n\n**Description:**\nThe code correctly checks `typeof classes === 'string'` at lines 183 and 198 before regex operations. However, for SVG elements, `element.className` returns an `SVGAnimatedString` object, not a string. The initial assignment `var classes = element.className || ''` would produce the SVGAnimatedString object (truthy), and the `typeof` check correctly excludes it.\n\nThis is actually well-handled -- noting it for completeness. The code correctly falls through to `origin: 'unknown'` for SVG elements, which is the right behavior.\n\n**No fix needed.**\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 7: Prototype Chain Traversal in `findReactFiberKeys`\n\n**Severity: LOW**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 234-243\n\n**Description:**\n`Object.keys(element)` only returns own enumerable properties, which is correct and safe against prototype pollution. If `Object.prototype` were polluted with a property starting with `__reactFiber$`, `Object.keys` would NOT include it. This is correctly implemented.\n\n**Cross-reference:** `inspector.js` line 48 uses the same pattern, also correctly.\n\n**No fix needed.**\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 8: Information Disclosure via `detectStyleOrigin` Return Values\n\n**Severity: LOW**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 147-153, 157-168\n\n**Description:**\n`detectStyleOrigin` returns component names, prop values, and theme defaults. In the `mantine-prop` origin case, it returns the raw prop value from `owner.memoizedProps[candidates[ci]]`, which could be any JavaScript value (not just a string token name). This data flows via `postToParent` through the inspector to the panel frame.\n\nIf a Mantine component has `p={sensitiveComputedValue}` where the value is derived from user data, that value gets included in the style origin result and sent cross-frame.\n\n**Mitigating factors:** The postMessage target is the sidecar origin (controlled by the developer's local proxy), not an external origin. The data stays within the editing tool's frames.\n\n**Fix:** Consider coercing the returned `value` to a string or known token name:\n```javascript\nreturn {\n  origin: 'mantine-prop',\n  prop: candidates[ci],\n  value: String(owner.memoizedProps[candidates[ci]]),\n  component: compName,\n};\n```\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 9: Cross-Frame Trust Boundary — `themeDefaults` from `window.__ZEROFOG__`\n\n**Severity: LOW**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 97-103\n\n**Description:**\nWhen `themeDefaults` is not explicitly passed, the function reads from `window.__ZEROFOG__.themeDefaults`. Since `toolbar.js` runs in the target application's frame, any code in that application can write to `window.__ZEROFOG__.themeDefaults` and influence style origin detection.\n\n```javascript\nvar _themeDefaults =\n  themeDefaults !== undefined\n    ? themeDefaults\n    : (typeof window !== 'undefined' &&\n        window.__ZEROFOG__ &&\n        window.__ZEROFOG__.themeDefaults) ||\n      {};\n```\n\nA malicious or buggy component could set:\n```javascript\nwindow.__ZEROFOG__.themeDefaults = { Card: { padding: 'xl' } };\n```\n\nThis would cause `detectStyleOrigin` to report `mantine-default` origins with attacker-controlled values, potentially misleading the visual editor into making incorrect source code changes.\n\n**Mitigating factors:** This is a same-origin attack within the developer's own application. The target app already has full script execution, so this is not a privilege escalation. However, it could cause incorrect edits.\n\n**Fix:** Freeze `themeDefaults` after initial setup, or validate the shape of the data:\n```javascript\n// In inspector.js initialization:\nwindow.__ZEROFOG__.themeDefaults = Object.freeze(themeDefaults || {});\n```\n\n---\n\n## FINDING 10: `componentChain[0]` Used as Raw Selector String\n\n**Severity: MEDIUM**\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js`, lines 216-219\n\n**Description:**\nWhen `testId` is falsy but `componentChain` exists, `finalizeDiff` uses `selection.componentChain[0]` as the `elementSelector`:\n\n```javascript\n: selection.componentChain && selection.componentChain.length > 0\n    ? selection.componentChain[0]\n    : 'unknown';\n```\n\n`componentChain[0]` comes from React fiber `type.displayName || type.name`. A component could set `displayName` to a valid CSS selector string like `\"* { display: none !important; }\"` or `\".sensitive-data\"`. If this selector is later used in `document.querySelector()` or for CSS override construction, it could match unintended elements.\n\n**Attack Scenario:**\n1. A component sets `displayName = '*, body'`.\n2. User selects an element under that component, no `data-testid` present.\n3. `finalizeDiff` returns `elementSelector: '*, body'`.\n4. In Phase 5, if this selector is used in `querySelector` or CSS rule construction, it matches every element on the page.\n\n**Fix:** Validate that componentChain entries match expected component name patterns:\n```javascript\nfunction isSafeComponentName(name) {\n  return typeof name === 'string' && /^[A-Z][A-Za-z0-9.]+$/.test(name);\n}\n\nvar fallbackSelector = 'unknown';\nif (selection.componentChain && selection.componentChain.length > 0) {\n  var candidate = selection.componentChain[0];\n  if (isSafeComponentName(candidate)) {\n    fallbackSelector = candidate;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| # | Finding | Severity | Exploitable? | Fix Effort |\n|---|---------|----------|-------------|------------|\n| 1 | Selector injection in `finalizeDiff` via unescaped `testId` | HIGH | Yes, when diff is consumed downstream | Trivial — add `escapeAttrValue` |\n| 2 | ReDoS potential in Tailwind regex (lazy `\\S+?` in brackets) | MEDIUM | Requires crafted className, O(n^2) | Low — use `[^\\]]+` instead of `\\S+?` |\n| 3 | Prototype key collision in themeDefaults lookup via fiber displayName | MEDIUM | Requires prototype pollution + crafted fiber | Low — add `hasOwnProperty` check |\n| 4 | Missing null/type validation on public function inputs | MEDIUM | DoS via TypeError crash | Low — add guards |\n| 5 | CSS variable oracle via sentinel element timing | LOW | Theoretical, values already public | Low — use root element instead |\n| 6 | SVG className handling | N/A | Correctly handled | None |\n| 7 | Prototype chain in `findReactFiberKeys` | N/A | Correctly handled via `Object.keys` | None |\n| 8 | Prop value disclosure in style origin results | LOW | Mitigated by local-only postMessage target | Trivial — stringify values |\n| 9 | `window.__ZEROFOG__.themeDefaults` writable by target app | LOW | Same-origin, no privilege escalation | Low — freeze object |\n| 10 | Raw component name used as fallback selector | MEDIUM | When consumed as CSS selector downstream | Low — validate pattern |\n\n## Prioritized Remediation\n\n**Must fix before shipping:**\n1. **Finding 1** — Add `escapeAttrValue` to `finalizeDiff`. This is a concrete injection that will become exploitable the moment Phase 5 consumes the diff selector.\n2. **Finding 10** — Validate or sanitize the component name fallback selector for the same reason.\n3. **Finding 4** — Add input validation guards. Crashes during editing are a poor user experience.\n\n**Should fix:**\n4. **Finding 2** — Replace `\\[\\S+?\\]` with `\\[[^\\]]+\\]` in all four Tailwind patterns.\n5. **Finding 3** — Add `hasOwnProperty` check on themeDefaults lookup.\n\n**Nice to have:**\n6. **Finding 5** — Eliminate sentinel element, read from root computed style.\n7. **Finding 8** — Coerce prop values to strings.\n8. **Finding 9** — Freeze `themeDefaults` after initialization.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>40589</total_tokens><tool_uses>9</tool_uses><duration_ms>127577</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-derricklee-cortex/tasks/a3d9de7c89660c21e.output",
