          "type": "user",
          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a6aef187359e35976</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01B4hM9119bzWZN1kA5fJUHW</tool-use-id>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Frontend review of toolbar\" completed</summary>\n<result>Good. Now I have the complete picture. Here is the deep technical review.\n\n---\n\n# Deep Technical Review: toolbar.js, toolbar.d.ts, toolbar.test.ts\n\n## Architecture Summary\n\n`toolbar.js` is a pure-function module providing design token resolution and style origin detection. It is *not* included in the tsup IIFE build (the build entry points are `panel.tsx`, `inspector.js`, `nav-blocker.js`). It is not imported by any other source file. It exists as a standalone ESM module consumed only by its test file. `inspector.js` is the runtime client that shares duplicated functions (`findReactFiberKeys`, fiber traversal logic). The two files operate in separate IIFE scopes at runtime.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Findings\n\n### C1. toolbar.js is dead code -- not built, not imported, not injected\n\n**Files:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/tsup.config.ts` (lines 15-18), `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/inject.ts` (lines 3-7)\n\nThe tsup config builds `panel.tsx`, `inspector.js`, and `nav-blocker.js` as IIFE client bundles. `toolbar.js` is not listed as an entry point. `inject.ts` only injects `inspector.js` and `nav-blocker.js`. No file in `src/` imports from `toolbar.js`. The only consumer is `toolbar.test.ts`.\n\n**Impact:** Every function in `toolbar.js` -- `buildTokenMaps`, `reverseTokenLookup`, `detectStyleOrigin`, `finalizeDiff` -- is unreachable at runtime. The 645-line test suite validates logic that will never execute in a user's browser. If this module is intended to be consumed by the panel or injected alongside the inspector, that integration is completely missing. If it is intended as a future library, it should at minimum be documented as such.\n\n**Fix:** Either (a) add `toolbar.js` to the tsup `entry` array and inject it, or (b) import it from `panel.tsx` so it gets bundled into the panel IIFE, or (c) explicitly mark it as a future/unused module with a clear TODO. As-is, the entire review below covers code that has no runtime path.\n\n### C2. React 19 fiber traversal in detectStyleOrigin uses `fiber.return` but conflates \"owner\" with \"parent\"\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (lines 110-173)\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` (lines 62-95)\n\nThe code's dual-strategy comment says \"React 18 uses `_debugOwner`, React 19 uses `fiber.return`.\" This is fundamentally incorrect about what these represent. `_debugOwner` points to the **component that rendered this element** (the JSX author). `fiber.return` points to the **parent in the fiber tree**, which includes every wrapper: `Fragment`, `Suspense`, `ErrorBoundary`, `Context.Provider`, `memo`, `forwardRef`, etc.\n\nIn `detectStyleOrigin` (lines 123-173), when `useDebugOwner` is false, the code walks `owner = owner.return` skipping fibers with `tag !== 0 && tag !== 1`. This misses:\n\n- **tag 11** (`ForwardRef`): Mantine's `Button`, `TextInput`, and nearly every component use `React.forwardRef`. These produce fibers with tag 11, not 0 or 1. The component name and `memoizedProps` live on the ForwardRef fiber. By skipping tag 11, the code will walk right past every forwarded Mantine component.\n- **tag 15** (`SimpleMemoComponent`): Components wrapped in `React.memo`.\n- **tag 14** (`MemoComponent`): Components wrapped in `React.memo` with custom comparison.\n\nThe inspector.js `walkComponentChain` (line 87) has the same problem: `currentB.tag === 0 || currentB.tag === 1` skips ForwardRef/Memo fibers.\n\n**Impact:** On React 19, `detectStyleOrigin` will almost never find Mantine component props because virtually all Mantine components use `forwardRef`. The function will fall through to the Tailwind/CSS-module/unknown checks, returning incorrect origin data. The inspector's component chain will be missing most Mantine component names.\n\n**Fix:** Expand the tag filter to include tags 11 (ForwardRef) and 14/15 (Memo variants):\n```javascript\nif (!useDebugOwner && owner.tag !== 0 && owner.tag !== 1 \n    && owner.tag !== 11 && owner.tag !== 14 && owner.tag !== 15) {\n```\n\nAlso note: React fiber tag values are internal and undocumented. They have changed between versions. Hardcoding them is fragile. A more resilient approach would be to check `typeof fiber.type === 'function'` or `fiber.type && (fiber.type.$$typeof || fiber.type.render)`.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Findings\n\n### H1. buildTokenMaps calls getComputedStyle per property per token -- forces layout for every read\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (lines 44-57)\n\nInside the loop, the code sets `sentinel.style.padding`, then reads `getComputedStyle(sentinel).paddingTop`, then sets `sentinel.style.borderRadius`, then reads `getComputedStyle(sentinel).borderTopLeftRadius`. That is 10 style-write + getComputedStyle pairs (2 per iteration x 5 sizes). Each `getComputedStyle` after a style mutation triggers a **synchronous layout reflow**.\n\n**Impact:** 10 forced reflows on every call to `buildTokenMaps`. If called during page load or HMR, this creates a layout thrash burst. On complex pages, each reflow can take 5-50ms, meaning 50-500ms of jank.\n\n**Fix:** Batch all style writes, then batch all reads:\n```javascript\n// Phase 1: Write all styles\nvar sentinels = [];\nfor (var i = 0; i < TOOLBAR_SIZES.length; i++) {\n  var s = document.createElement('div');\n  s.style.cssText = 'position:absolute;visibility:hidden;pointer-events:none;width:0;height:0';\n  s.style.padding = 'var(--mantine-spacing-' + TOOLBAR_SIZES[i] + ')';\n  s.style.borderRadius = 'var(--mantine-radius-' + TOOLBAR_SIZES[i] + ')';\n  document.body.appendChild(s);\n  sentinels.push(s);\n}\n// Phase 2: Read all computed values (single reflow