|\\[\\S+?\\])/`\n\nMissing cases:\n- **Tailwind `!` important modifier**: `!p-4` is valid Tailwind syntax (and `!` can also appear after the prefix: `sm:!p-4`). The regex does not account for `!`.\n- **Tailwind v4**: Uses a different class naming convention with CSS-native approach. Classes may be authored differently.\n- **`p-0`**: The regex requires a hyphen followed by `\\d+(?:\\.5)?|px|auto|...`, and `\\d+` matches `0`, so `p-0` works. However, just `rounded` without a suffix (bare `rounded` class) -- the border-radius pattern handles this with the `?` at the end of the capture group, returning `undefined` for the match group, but `match[0].trim()` returns `'rounded'`. This actually works correctly.\n- **Larger Tailwind values**: `p-96`, `gap-96` etc. are valid. These match `\\d+` so they work.\n- **Spacing scale values like `p-1.5`, `p-2.5`, `p-3.5`**: The regex only allows `.5` after digits, so `p-1.5` would match capturing `1.5` -- wait, `(?:\\.5)?` only matches `.5`, not `.5` after multi-digit. Actually `\\d+(?:\\.5)?` would match `1` then optionally `.5`, so `1.5` matches. But `2.5` would match as `2` with `.5` optional... no, `\\d+` is greedy and matches `2`, then `(?:\\.5)?` matches `.5`. So `2.5` works. Good.\n\n**The actual bug**: the `rounded` regex `/(?:^|\\s)(?:[\\w-]+:)*rounded(?:-(none|sm|md|lg|xl|2xl|3xl|full|\\[\\S+?\\]))?/` does NOT match `rounded-t-lg`, `rounded-bl-sm`, etc. (per-corner/per-side radius classes). These are commonly used.\n\n**Impact:** Per-side Tailwind border-radius classes would not be detected, falling through to CSS Module or unknown.\n\n**Fix:** Extend the rounded regex to handle directional variants:\n```javascript\n'border-radius':\n  /(?:^|\\s)(?:[\\w-]+:)*rounded(?:-(?:t|b|l|r|tl|tr|bl|br|s|e|ss|se|es|ee))?(?:-(none|sm|md|lg|xl|2xl|3xl|full|\\[\\S+?\\]))?/\n```\n\n### H4. Selector in finalizeDiff falls back to bare component name -- not a valid CSS selector\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (lines 214-228)\n\nWhen `selection.testId` is falsy and `componentChain` has entries, the selector becomes `selection.componentChain[0]` -- e.g., `\"Card\"`. This is a bare string, not a valid CSS selector. If downstream code uses this with `document.querySelector(selector)`, it will select a `<Card>` HTML element (which does not exist) rather than doing anything useful.\n\n**Impact:** Any diff created without a `data-testid` will have an unusable `elementSelector`. If this feeds into Claude's code translation layer or the override CSS system, it will silently fail.\n\n**Fix:** Either (a) use the `buildSelector` function from inspector.js to generate a real CSS selector (requires DOM access, breaking the \"pure function\" contract), or (b) use a structured format that explicitly signals it is a component reference, not a CSS selector: `{ type: 'component', name: 'Card' }` vs `{ type: 'selector', value: '[data-testid=\"...\"]' }`. Or (c) require the caller to always provide a valid selector via the selection object.\n\n### H5. The `_debugOwner` existence check is correct for React 18 but the `fiber.return` fallback is overly aggressive for React 16/17\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (lines 110-118)\n\nThe comment says \"React 18 uses `_debugOwner`, React 19 uses `fiber.return`.\" In reality:\n- React 16-18: `_debugOwner` exists on fiber nodes\n- React 19: `_debugOwner` removed; `_debugInfo` introduced for server components\n\nThe `hasOwnProperty` check on line 111 correctly distinguishes the two. However, if a DOM fiber in React 16/17 happens to not have `_debugOwner` as an own property (e.g., production builds where debug info is stripped), the code falls through to the `fiber.return` path, which would walk the parent fiber tree, producing inflated and incorrect component chains that include every wrapper in the tree.\n\n**Impact:** In production builds of React 16-18, `_debugOwner` may not exist, causing the return-path traversal to fire. This would yield chains like `['div', 'Fragment', 'Suspense', 'App']` instead of `['Card', 'Dashboard']`.\n\n**Fix:** Add an explicit check for production mode. If `__reactFiber$` keys exist but neither `_debugOwner` nor meaningful component names are found, return early rather than walking `fiber.return` in a context where it produces garbage. Alternatively, check for `_debugInfo` to positively identify React 19.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Findings\n\n### M1. Duplicated `findReactFiberKeys` between toolbar.js and inspector.js will drift\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (lines 234-243)\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` (lines 46-55)\n\nThe functions are identical. The comment on line 233 of toolbar.js says \"Intentional duplicate -- IIFEs are independent at runtime.\" This is architecturally reasonable for IIFE isolation, but since toolbar.js is *not* an IIFE entry point (see C1), the duplication has no runtime justification. Even if toolbar.js were built as a separate IIFE, the implementations could drift. The React 19 dual-strategy logic is also duplicated between the two files (`detectStyleOrigin` in toolbar.js vs `walkComponentChain` in inspector.js), but with subtle differences in the tag-skipping logic.\n\n**Impact:** Bug fixes applied to one copy may not propagate to the other. The React 19 tag filtering is already slightly different: `walkComponentChain` filters `tag === 0 || tag === 1`, while `detectStyleOrigin` filters `owner.tag !== 0 && owner.tag !== 1`. Same logic, inverse expression -- but if one is updated to include tag 11, the other might be missed.\n\n**Fix:** Extract shared functions into a `shared.js` that both entry points import. tsup will inline it into each IIFE bundle, achieving the isolation goal without source duplication.\n\n### M2. `detectStyleOrigin` Mantine prop check uses `!== undefined` -- will miss `null` and falsy prop value