ction.\n\n**Fix:** Add a test case:\n```javascript\nit('handles SVGAnimatedString className without throwing', () => {\n  const element = createMockElement({ className: { baseVal: 'cls', animVal: 'cls' } });\n  const result = detectStyleOrigin(element, 'padding', () => []);\n  expect(result.origin).toBe('unknown');\n});\n```\n\n### M5. `buildTokenMaps` test mock assumes specific call ordering that couples to implementation\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/tests/client/toolbar.test.ts` (lines 63-94)\n\nThe mock `styleGetter` uses a `callCount` variable and determines which size/property to return based on modular arithmetic (`Math.floor(callCount / 2)`, `callCount % 2`). This creates a fragile coupling to the exact order of style reads in `buildTokenMaps`. If the implementation changes to batch writes and reads (as recommended in H1), every mock in this test suite breaks.\n\n**Impact:** The test suite would block the performance fix in H1.\n\n**Fix:** Use a mock that inspects the sentinel element's style to determine what was set, rather than relying on call order:\n```javascript\nconst mockStyleGetter = function(el) {\n  // Read back which CSS variable was set\n  const padding = el.style.padding;\n  const radius = el.style.borderRadius;\n  // Return based on what was written\n  // ...\n};\n```\n\n### M6. `escapeAttrValue` in inspector.js does not escape single quotes\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` (lines 37-39)\n\nThe function escapes `\\` and `\"`. The generated selectors use double quotes (`[data-testid=\"...\"]`), so single quotes inside values are not a parsing issue. However, if a testId contains a newline, null byte, or other control character, the selector would be malformed.\n\n**Impact:** Low -- `data-testid` values are developer-controlled. The doc comment (lines 33-36) explicitly acknowledges this limitation.\n\n**Fix:** None required, but consider `CSS.escape()` if browser support allows it (available since Chrome 46, Firefox 31, Safari 10).\n\n---\n\n## LOW Findings\n\n### L1. `RADIUS_SIZES` includes 'none' but `TOOLBAR_SIZES` does not -- inconsistency is undocumented\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (lines 14-15)\n\n`TOOLBAR_SIZES = ['xs', 'sm', 'md', 'lg', 'xl']` is used as the iteration set for both spacing and radius in `buildTokenMaps`. `RADIUS_SIZES = ['none', 'xs', 'sm', 'md', 'lg', 'xl']` is exported but never used internally. The 'none' value is handled by the hardcoded `radiusMap['0px'] = 'none'` on line 65.\n\n**Impact:** A consumer might use `RADIUS_SIZES` assuming it maps 1:1 to the token map, but 'none' is actually handled differently. No functional bug, but a source of confusion.\n\n**Fix:** Add a comment on `RADIUS_SIZES` explaining that 'none' maps to 0px and is handled specially.\n\n### L2. `reverseTokenLookup` threshold of 1000px for 'full' is arbitrary\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (lines 78-80)\n\nThe `border-radius: 9999px` convention (used by Tailwind and Mantine for \"full\" pill shapes) is detected by checking `num > 1000`. This works for common cases but would false-positive on legitimately large radius values on oversized elements.\n\n**Impact:** Negligible in practice.\n\n**Fix:** Use `>= 9999` or `>= 999` as a more precise threshold if desired.\n\n### L3. `parseOverrideRules` does not handle CSS comments\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` (lines 283-341)\n\nThe character-by-character parser does not strip `/* ... */` comments. If override CSS contains comments, they would be parsed as part of selectors or property values.\n\n**Impact:** Low -- override CSS is programmatically generated, not hand-authored.\n\n**Fix:** Add a comment-stripping pass before parsing, or document the no-comments constraint.\n\n### L4. `finalizeDiff` uses `new Date().toISOString()` -- not mockable in tests\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.js` (line 226)\n\nThe timestamp is generated inside the function. Tests only assert `expect(diff.timestamp).toBeDefined()` rather than checking the value. This is fine for now, but if timestamp accuracy matters later, the function would need a clock injection parameter.\n\n**Impact:** None currently.\n\n### L5. TypeScript declaration file type for `element` parameter is too loose\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/toolbar.d.ts` (line 44)\n\n`element: Record<string, unknown>` loses all DOM type information. Callers get no autocompletion for `.className`, `.getAttribute()`, etc. The inspector.d.ts uses the same loose type.\n\n**Impact:** Developer experience only.\n\n**Fix:** Use `Element & Record<string, unknown>` or a custom `DOMElementWithFiber` type.\n\n---\n\n## Positive Practices Worth Preserving\n\n1. **Dependency injection throughout.** `buildTokenMaps(styleGetter)`, `detectStyleOrigin(element, property, findFiberKeysFn, themeDefaults)` -- every external dependency is injectable. This makes the functions testable without a real browser DOM. This is excellent API design for a DevTools library.\n\n2. **The `hasOwnProperty` check for `_debugOwner`** (toolbar.js line 111, inspector.js line 70). This is the correct approach. A truthiness check (`if (fiber._debugOwner)`) would fail when `_debugOwner` is `null` (React 18 leaf components), incorrectly falling through to the React 19 path. The `Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call()` form avoids prototype chain pollution. This shows understanding of a subtle React internals edge case.\n\n3. **The sentinel cleanup pattern** in `buildTokenMaps` (try/finally on lines 44-62). Even if `getComputedStyle` throws, the sentinel is removed. The test on line 111 specifically validates this.\n\n4. **The `data-zerofog-ui` attribute exclusion pattern** in inspector.js (e.g., line 545). Preventing the inspector's own overlay elements from bei