            "new_string": "**Performance note:** One MutationObserver per overridden Tailwind **element** (not per override). The `tailwindObservers` map uses a single observer per element regardless of how many Tailwind properties are overridden. With the 50-element cap on `elementMap`, this is bounded at 50 observers maximum. Each observes a single attribute on a single element — negligible overhead. A single class mutation triggers one observer callback that re-applies all overrides for that element in a single pass (O(N) in overrides, not O(N²)).\n\n#### 5b-i. JIT Class Existence Check\n\nModern Tailwind (v3+) uses JIT compilation — CSS rules are only generated for classes found in source files at build time. Swapping `p-4` → `p-8` on a live element adds the class attribute, but if `p-8` was never in the source, no corresponding `.p-8 { padding: 2rem }` rule exists in the stylesheet. The swap silently has no effect.\n\n**Detection + fallback after class swap:**\n\n```javascript\n// After adding newClass to element:\nfunction verifyTailwindClassEffect(el, cssProperty, newClass) {\n  var before = window.getComputedStyle(el).getPropertyValue(cssProperty);\n  // Class was already added by apply() — check if style actually changed\n  // If computed value is unchanged, the JIT class doesn't exist in the stylesheet\n  if (before === window.getComputedStyle(el).getPropertyValue(cssProperty)) {\n    // Inject a <style> tag with the needed utility CSS rule\n    var ruleId = '__zerofog_tw_' + newClass.replace(/[^a-z0-9-]/gi, '_');\n    if (!document.getElementById(ruleId)) {\n      var style = document.createElement('style');\n      style.id = ruleId;\n      style.setAttribute('data-zerofog-ui', 'true');\n      // Generate the CSS rule that Tailwind would have generated\n      style.textContent = '.' + CSS.escape(newClass) + ' { ' + cssProperty + ': ' + resolveTailwindValue(newClass) + ' }';\n      document.head.appendChild(style);\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Note:** `resolve