            "new_string": "## Appendix: Architecture Review Audit Trail (2026-03-02)\n\n**Review team:** frontend, security, design, mts, performance (5 personas × 2 modes = 10 reviewers)\n**Mode:** both (clink + native) — Claude, Gemini, Codex backends\n**Result:** 4 CRITICALs, 8 HIGHs, 10 MEDIUMs, 7 LOWs → all CRITICAL/HIGH findings incorporated into spec\n\n### Cross-Reviewer Consensus (3+ independent flags)\n\n| # | Issue | Resolution | Spec Section |\n|---|-------|-----------|--------------|\n| 1 | `deactivate()` ordering: elementMap cleared before override cleanup | Fixed — overrides cleanup now step 2, elementMap step 5 | §6.3, Phase 15 |\n| 2 | Tailwind JIT class non-existence | Fixed — `verifyTailwindClassEffect` + `<style>` injection | §5b-i |\n| 3 | Selection overlay scroll drift | Fixed — passive scroll/resize listeners reposition overlay | Phase 19 |\n| 4 | React 19 `_debugOwner` removal breaks fiber walk | Fixed — version-adaptive `walkComponentChain` | §8.5 |\n| 5 | MutationObserver O(N²) cascade per element | Fixed — single-observer-per-element via `tailwindObservers` map | §5b |\n| 6 | HMR destroys Tailwind preview state | Fixed — body-level observer auto-reapplies on element re-creation | §8.3 |\n| 7 | `resolveSource` repeated per hover without caching | Fixed — cached in `elementMap[selId]._cachedSource` | §3 table, Phase 5 |\n\n### Positive Practices (preserved)\n\nStrategy dispatch pattern · CSS variable references for Mantine · Dual storage model (`overrideRules` + `overrideRecords`) · `detectStyleOrigin` cascade priority · Reconciliation survival via `<style>` tag · Idempotent injection marker · Origin validation in postMessage · Explicit limitation documentation\n\n### MEDIUM/LOW items (not incorporated — tracked separately)\n\n10 MEDIUM findings (iframe sandbox trust model, CSP rewriting docs, `elementFromPoint` reliability, overlay flicker, panel placeholder, token vocabulary, `cssValue` overloading, sentinel reflows, serial script loading, `targetOrigin` narrowing) and 7 LOW findings remain as future work. These do not affect correctness or v1 viability.\n\n### Methodology\n\nBoth-mode review (clink + native) justified its cost: clink caught proxy buffering + DNS rebinding + SPA race; native caught CSS Module hash instability + undo gap + trust model. All 7 consensus items surfaced independently in both modes.",
            "old_string": "## Architecture Review Findings (2026-03-02)\n\n**Review team:** frontend, security, design, mts (Master Technical Strategist), performance\n**Selection rationale:** Section 14's 20-phase UX flow is DOM/CSS-heavy (frontend), relies on cross-frame postMessage (security), defines the entire user interaction model (design), involves intricate state management and edge cases (mts), and has hot-path operations like hover/scroll (performance).\n**Mode:** both (clink + native — 10 total reviewers)\n\n---\n\n### Cross-Reviewer Consensus\n\nIssues flagged independently by 3+ reviewers — highest-confidence signals:\n\n| # | Issue | Flagged By | Severity |\n|---|-------|-----------|----------|\n| 1 | **`deactivate()` ordering bug**: `elementMap.clear()` runs before `overrideRecords` cleanup, so Tailwind MutationObservers never disconnect — memory leak and ghost observers | ALL 10 reviewers | CRITICAL |\n| 2 | **Tailwind JIT class non-existence**: Swapping to a class not in the original build (e.g., `p-8` when only `p-4` was used) silently fails — the class has no corresponding CSS rule in the JIT-generated stylesheet | frontend (×2), mts (×2), performance, design | CRITICAL |\n| 3 | **Selection overlay doesn't track scroll**: Green overlay positioned at click-time viewport coordinates becomes visually misaligned after scroll. No scroll/resize handler exists. | frontend (×2), design (×2), mts, performance | HIGH |\n| 4 | **React 19 breaks `detectStyleOrigin` for Mantine**: `_debugOwner` removed in React 19; the fiber traversal in `walkComponentChain` that identifies Mantine props will silently return empty results, making all Mantine elements fall to CSS `!important` path | frontend (×2), mts (×2) | CRITICAL |\n| 5 | **MutationObserver cascade with multiple Tailwind overrides**: Each Tailwind override on the same element adds a new observer. Multiple observers fire O(N²) times during class attribute changes, each re-applying all overrides. | frontend (×2), mts (×2), performance | HIGH |\n| 6 | **HMR silently destroys Tailwind preview state**: Hot module replacement re-renders components, which can reset className to the pre-override value. MutationObserver will re-apply, but there's a visible flash and no guarantee of ordering. | frontend, mts (×2) | HIGH |\n| 7 | **`updateOverrideSheet()` called on every hover without batching**: Each hover triggers `resolveSource` → `postMessage` → panel update, but the override sheet is also rebuilt. No RAF/microtask batching. | performance (×2), mts | HIGH |\n\n---\n\n### Consolidated Findings by Severity\n\n#### CRITICAL — Must fix before v1\n\n**C1. `deactivate()` resource leak (consensus #1)**\n\nThe spec's deactivation sequence clears `elementMap` before iterating `overrideRecords` to disconnect MutationObservers and revert Tailwind classes. Since records reference elements via `elementMap`, the cleanup loop finds nothing — observers leak, reverted classes never restore.\n\n*Fix:* Reverse the ordering. Process `overrideRecords` first (disconnect observers, revert classes), then clear `elementMap` and `overrideRules`.\n\n**C2. Tailwind JIT renders class-swap strategy non-functional for most projects (consensus #2)**\n\nModern Tailwind (v3+) only generates CSS for classes found in source files at build time. Swapping `p-4` → `p-8` on a live element adds the `p-8` class but there is no corresponding `.p-8 { padding: 2rem }` rule in the stylesheet. The element silently keeps its old padding.\n\n*Fix:* Three options (not mutually exclusive): (a) inject a `<style>` tag with the needed utility rule at override time (most reliable), (b) detect JIT mode and fall back to CSS `!important` with an \"approximate\" flag, (c) require a Tailwind CDN/play mode during editing sessions. Option (a) is recommended — it preserves native rendering semantics while ensuring the rule exists.\n\n**C3. React 19 compatibility break in `detectStyleOrigin` (consensus #4)**\n\n`walkComponentChain` traverses React fibers via `_debugOwner` to find Mantine component props. React 19 removed `_debugOwner` in favor of `fiber.return` chains with different semantics. The spec doesn't address version detection or fallback.\n\n*Fix:* Implement a version-adaptive fiber walker: attempt `_debugOwner` first, fall back to `fiber.return` traversal. Add a `reactVersion` detection step during inspector initialization (check `React.version` or `__REACT_DEVTOOLS_GLOBAL_HOOK__`).\n\n**C4. Proxy full-body buffering for HTML responses (performance-clink only)**\n\nThe sidecar proxy buffers entire HTML response bodies to inject scripts and rewrite CSP headers. For large SSR pages (100KB+), this adds latency and memory pressure. Not consensus but flagged as P0 by performance reviewers.\n\n*Fix:* Use streaming HTML rewriting (e.g., `htmlparser2` SAX mode or a transform stream that injects before `</body>` without buffering the full body).\n\n#### HIGH — Should fix in v1\n\n**H1. Selection overlay scroll drift (consensus #3)**\n\nThe green selection overlay uses viewport-relative coordinates from `getBoundingClientRect()` at click time. After scroll, it floats at the old position. The spec acknowledges this in Phase 19 but proposes no solution beyond \"hide on scroll.\"\n\n*Fix:* Attach a passive `scroll` + `resize` listener on selection. On scroll, either (a) recompute `getBoundingClientRect()` and reposition, or (b) hide the overlay and show a \"re-hover to re-select\" hint.\n\n**H2. MutationObserver cascade (consensus #5)**\n\nEach Tailwind override creates its own `MutationObserver` on the element's `class` attribute. With N overrides, a single class change triggers N observer callbacks, each of which may modify the class list, triggering further callbacks.\n\n*Fix:* Use a single observer per element. Maintain a `Map<Element, Set<OverrideRecord>>` so one observer can re-apply all Tailwind overrides for that element in a single pass.\n\n**H3. HMR destroys Tailwind preview state (consensus #6)**\n\nWhen HMR replaces a module, React re-renders the component tree. New elements get the original className (without overrides). The MutationObserver on the old element is disconnected (element removed from DOM). Overrides are lost until the user re-applies.\n\n*Fix:* After HMR, re-walk `overrideRecords` and re-apply any Tailwind overrides whose target elements have been replaced. Use a `MutationObserver` on the document body watching for subtree additions that match stored selectors.\n\n**H4. Hover hot-path unbatched (consensus #7)**\n\nEach hover: `elementFromPoint` → `resolveSource` (walks fiber tree) → `postMessage` → panel update → `updateOverrideSheet()`. No debounce or RAF batching. Rapid mouse movement causes jank.\n\n*Fix:* Debounce hover processing with `requestAnimationFrame`. Skip if the hovered element hasn't changed. Cache `resolveSource` results per element (invalidate on HMR).\n\n**H5. `buildSelector` recomputed on every override application (performance)**\n\nThe selector construction (data attribute or generated class) runs every time an override is applied, even for elements that already have a stable selector.\n\n*Fix:* Cache selectors in `elementMap` entries. Compute once on first override, reuse thereafter.\n\n**H6. CSS Module hash instability (frontend-native)**\n\nCSS Module class names include content hashes that change on file edit. Selectors built from these classes break silently after HMR updates the stylesheet. Overrides targeting `.Button_root_a1b2c` stop matching when the hash changes to `.Button_root_x3y4z`.\n\n*Fix:* For CSS Module elements, prefer data-attribute selectors (which are stable across rebuilds) over class-based selectors. The spec's `buildSelector` should deprioritize CSS Module class names.\n\n**H7. No undo/redo (design-native)**\n\nThe spec describes accumulating overrides but provides no mechanism to undo individual changes or redo reverted ones. Users must remove overrides one property at a time.\n\n*Fix:* Implement an undo stack in the panel. Each override application pushes a `{ element, property, previousValue, newValue }` entry. Undo pops and reverses. This is a v1 usability requirement.\n\n**H8. `resolveSource` repeated per hover (performance)**\n\n`resolveSource` walks the React fiber tree and calls `getComputedStyle` for every hover event, even if the element is already in `elementMap` with a known classification.\n\n*Fix:* Cache `resolveSource` results keyed by element reference. Invalidate on HMR or DOM mutation.\n\n#### MEDIUM\n\n- **`allow-same-origin` on iframe negates sandbox isolation** — Design tradeoff (needed for script injection), but document should explicitly acknowledge the trust model and justify why same-origin is required (security-native)\n- **Session token exposed in postMessage** — `sessionId` is generated via `crypto.randomUUID()` which is adequate, but if the iframe loads a third-party script, that script can read all postMessages. Consider narrowing `targetOrigin` from `'*'` (security-clink, security-native)\n- **CSP header rewriting removes protections** — The proxy strips/rewrites CSP to allow injected scripts. Document which CSP directives are preserved and which are relaxed (security-clink)\n- **`elementFromPoint` unreliable for overlapping elements** — Hover detection misses elements under overlays, z-indexed layers, or pointer-events:none elements (frontend-native)\n- **Overlay flicker during rapid hover** — No debounce between hover target changes causes overlay repositioning jank (frontend-clink, design-clink)\n- **Panel is a placeholder `export {}`** — The entire right-side panel (token selector, property editor, diff preview) is unimplemented. The UX flow describes interactions with a panel that doesn't exist yet (design-native, mts-native)\n- **Token vocabulary limited to spacing + radius** — Only `padding`, `margin`, `gap`, `border-radius` are covered. Typography tokens, color tokens, and shadow tokens are not addressed (design-clink, design-native)\n- **`cssValue` field semantically overloaded** — For Mantine: it's a CSS variable reference. For Tailwind: it's a class name. For fallback: it's a pixel value. No type discrimination in the data model (mts-native)\n- **`buildTokenMaps()` triggers sentinel reflows** — Setting inline styles to detect token values causes layout recalculation for each property probed (performance-native)\n- **Serial script loading** — `inspector.js` and `nav-blocker.js` load sequentially. Should use `async` or combine (performance-clink)\n\n#### LOW\n\n- **Auto-generated selector may orphan overrides** — Generated `data-zf-*` attributes could collide if the same component renders multiple instances (frontend-clink)\n- **`postMessage` listener not cleaned up on deactivation** — Window listener persists after editor deactivates (mts-native)\n- **No loading/progress indicator during `resolveSource`** — Fiber walk can take 5-10ms, during which the hover overlay shows stale data (design-native)\n- **`pushState`/`replaceState` race with SPA navigation** — Nav blocker intercepts history API but doesn't handle `popstate` events consistently (frontend-clink)\n- **Component name display depends on non-minified builds** — `fiber.type.displayName || fiber.type.name` returns minified names in production builds (frontend-native, mts-clink)\n- **DNS rebinding mitigated but not documented** — `server.ts` validates Host headers, but the threat model isn't documented in the spec (security-clink)\n- **Toolbar full DOM rebuild on every property change** — Each token selection rebuilds the toolbar HTML rather than updating in place (performance-native)\n\n---\n\n### Positive Practices — Preserve These\n\n1. **Strategy dispatch pattern** — The `mantineStrategy` / `tailwindStrategy` / `cssImportantStrategy` dispatch table is well-designed. Clean separation of concerns with a unified interface (`apply`, `revert`, `buildCSS`). Multiple reviewers praised this as the architectural highlight.\n\n2. **CSS variable references for Mantine** — Using `var(--mantine-spacing-lg)` instead of resolved pixel values preserves theme-switching fidelity. This is exactly the right approach and represents the core insight of the spec.\n\n3. **Dual storage model** — `overrideRules` (for CSS serialization) + `overrideRecords` (for strategy metadata and reversal) provides clean separation between rendering and undo concerns.\n\n4. **`detectStyleOrigin` cascade classification** — The priority ordering (mantine-prop > mantine-default > tailwind > css-module > unknown) correctly handles elements that match multiple framework patterns.\n\n5. **Reconciliation survival via `<style>` tag** — Placing Mantine CSS variable overrides in a `<style>` tag outside React's tree is the correct pattern. React reconciliation won't touch it, and it survives re-renders. This was praised by frontend, mts, and performance reviewers.\n\n6. **Idempotent injection** — The `MARKER` pattern in `inject.ts` prevents double-injection. Simple and correct.\n\n7. **Origin validation in postMessage** — `isValidInbound()` checks both origin and sessionId. The defense-in-depth approach is appropriate for the trust model.\n\n8. **Explicit acknowledgment of known limitations** — Phases 17-20 openly document edge cases (multi-edit conflicts, scroll drift, HMR destruction, dark mode interactions) rather than hiding them. This is good architectural practice.\n\n---\n\n### Review Methodology Note\n\n**Both mode** (clink + native) deployed 10 independent reviewers across 4 model backends (Claude, Gemini, Codex for clink; Claude for native).\n\n**What clink uniquely caught:**\n- Proxy body-buffering performance concern (performance-claude via clink)\n- Serial script loading optimization (performance-claude via clink)\n- DNS rebinding documentation gap (security-gemini via clink)\n- `pushState`/`replaceState` SPA race condition (frontend-claude via clink)\n\n**What native uniquely caught:**\n- CSS Module hash inst