, or move token resolution into the inspector (it runs in the iframe where `getComputedStyle` works).\n\n### H3. `handleMessage` only handles two message types -- not extensible for Phase 4a/4b/5\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` lines 430-439\n\n**Problem:** The message handler is a simple if/else for `inspector:enter-select` and `inspector:exit-select`. Phases 4a, 4b, and 5 will need at minimum:\n- `inspector:apply-override` (Phase 4a: apply a CSS token override to the selected element)\n- `inspector:revert-override` (Phase 4a: undo a specific override)\n- `inspector:revert-all` (Phase 4b: discard all overrides)\n- `inspector:query-token-maps` (Phase 4a: request CSS custom property resolution)\n- `inspector:preview-token` (Phase 4b: live preview a token change)\n- `inspector:block-navigation` / `inspector:unblock-navigation` (Phase 5)\n\nAdding these as chained if/else blocks will become unwieldy. More importantly, there's no dispatch pattern -- each new message type requires modifying the `handleMessage` function.\n\n**Impact:** Every downstream phase adds message types here. Without a dispatch table or registry pattern, this function becomes a growing switch statement that's hard to review and easy to introduce order-dependent bugs in.\n\n**Fix:** Replace with a dispatch table:\n```js\nvar messageHandlers = {\n  'inspector:enter-select': function() { selectMode = true; window.__ZEROFOG__.selectMode = true; },\n  'inspector:exit-select': function() { selectMode = false; window.__ZEROFOG__.selectMode = false; },\n};\n\nfunction handleMessage(e) {\n  if (!isValidInbound(e)) return;\n  var handler = messageHandlers[e.data.type];\n  if (handler) handler(e.data);\n}\n```\n\nThen Phase 4a/4b can extend via `messageHandlers['inspector:apply-override'] = function(msg) { ... }`.\n\n### H4. `postToParent` and `isValidInbound` are untestable -- no unit tests for the message protocol\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` lines 245-270\n\n**Problem:** `postToParent` and `isValidInbound` are pure(ish) functions but are not exported. They depend on module-level `SESSION_ID` and `SIDECAR_ORIGIN` template variables. The test file (`inspector.test.ts`) has zero tests for message validation.\n\n`isValidInbound` checks `e.origin === SIDECAR_ORIGIN` and `e.data.sessionId === SESSION_ID`. But `SESSION_ID` is the literal string `'{{SESSION_ID}}'` at import time in tests (the server template replacement doesn't happen). This means if these functions were tested, `isValidInbound` would reject everything unless the test crafted messages with `sessionId: '{{SESSION_ID}}'`.\n\n**Impact:** The message protocol is the boundary between inspector and panel -- it's the contract that Phase 4b depends on. Having zero test coverage of the validation logic means any change to the origin check or session matching could silently break cross-frame communication.\n\n**Fix:** Export `postToParent` and `isValidInbound`. Add tests:\n```ts\nit('rejects messages from wrong origin', () => { ... });\nit('rejects messages with wrong sessionId', () => { ... });\nit('accepts valid inbound messages', () => { ... });\n```\nConsider making `SESSION_ID` and `SIDECAR_ORIGIN` injectable (pass as parameters or set via `window.__ZEROFOG__` config) rather than relying on template string replacement.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM\n\n### M1. `isServerComponent` detection is a heuristic that produces false positives\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` lines 114, 134-137\n\n**Problem:** `isServerComponent` is set to `true` by default and flipped to `false` only when a `__reactFiber$` key is found on the element. This conflates \"no React fiber found\" with \"this is a React Server Component.\"\n\nFalse positives:\n- Plain HTML elements not rendered by React (e.g., elements in `<head>`, browser extension injections, Web Components)\n- Elements from other frameworks (Vue, Svelte, Angular)\n- React elements whose fiber keys haven't been assigned yet (hydration in progress)\n- Elements in `<noscript>` tags\n- The inspector's own overlay elements (these do have the `data-zerofog-ui` guard, but the naming is misleading)\n\nThe field name implies React RSC semantics, but it's really \"no fiber found.\" Phase 4b's panel would show \"Server Component\" when hovering over a plain `<div>` in the shell HTML.\n\n**Impact:** Misleading UI label in the panel. Low functional impact since the panel doesn't gate behavior on this flag yet, but it could mislead the user about why token editing isn't available for an element.\n\n**Fix:** Rename to `hasFiberData: boolean` or `clientRendered: boolean`. The negative case is \"unknown rendering origin,\" not \"server component.\"\n\n### M2. `classifyElement` is hardcoded to Mantine component names -- no extension point\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` lines 169-241\n\n**Problem:** The classification function has Mantine component names hardcoded in arrays: `['AppShell', 'Navbar', 'Header', ...]`. The implementation plan says target stack is \"React + Mantine (~80%), Tailwind (~17%), CSS Modules (~3%)\" -- so Mantine-specific detection makes sense for now.\n\nBut the classification is done by linear scan through multiple `indexOf` calls on array literals. Each `indexOf` on an array literal is O(n) and creates a new array on every call. For a hot path (called on every hover and click), this is wasteful.\n\nMore importantly, the Mantine-specific names are mixed into what should be a generic classification function. If the tool is ever used on a non-Mantine app (or the Mantine version changes component names), the classification silently falls to tag-based fallback, losing precision.\n\n**Impact:** Performance: minor (hover events are throttled by browser, and the arrays are small). Maintainability: the next person adding Chakra UI or Radix UI names has to edit the function body, not a configuration.\n\n**Fix:** Extract component-to-category mappings into a `Map` or plain object at module level:\n```js\nvar COMPONENT_CATEGORIES = {\n  'Button': 'interactive',\n  'AppShell': 'layout',\n  // ...\n};\n```\nThen the function becomes a single `Map.get()` lookup per chain entry.\n\n### M3. ES5 `var` declarations with ESM `export` syntax creates a confusing authoring contract\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` throughout\n\n**Problem:** The file uses ES5 `var` declarations and `function` statements (lines 17-18, 22-24, 28, etc.) but terminates with ESM `export { ... }` (lines 501-508). The comment on line 500 says \"stripped by tsup IIFE bundling\" -- so the exports exist only for testing.\n\nThe tsup config (`tsup.config.ts` line 18) bundles inspector.js as IIFE format targeting es2020. IIFE format wraps the module in `(function() { ... })()`, which means the `export` statements at the bottom are stripped or transformed.\n\nThis dual personality is fragile:\n- In test (vitest), it's imported as ESM -- `export` works, `var` declarations are module-scoped\n- In browser (tsup IIFE), exports are stripped, `var` declarations become function-scoped inside the IIFE wrapper\n- The template variables `SESSION_ID` and `SIDECAR_ORIGIN` (lines 17-18) need to be accessible to the IIFE's closure, which works because tsup's IIFE wrapper encompasses the entire file\n\n**Impact:** The next developer might add `const` or `let` declarations thinking \"it's ESM\" and get unexpected hoisting behavior differences between test and build. Or they might add an `import` statement (for a utility) which would break the IIFE bundling.\n\n**Fix:** Add a comment block at the file top explaining the dual-mode contract:\n```js\n/**\n * AUTHORING RULES:\n * 1. Use `var` and `function` declarations only (no const/let/import)\n * 2. The `export` block at bottom is for testing only -- tsup strips it for browser IIFE\n * 3. Template variables (SESSION_ID, SIDECAR_ORIGIN) are replaced by server at injection time\n * 4. Code inside the browser IIFE reads these via closure, not import\n */\n```\n\n### M4. `MSG_VERSION = 1` is declared but never validated on inbound messages\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` line 24 (declaration), line 263 (isValidInbound)\n\n**Problem:** `MSG_VERSION` is attached to outbound messages (line 256) but `isValidInbound` does not check `e.data.version === MSG_VERSION`. If the panel and inspector ever get out of sync (stale cached version in the browser), messages with incompatible schemas will be accepted silently.\n\n**Impact:** Today there's only one version, so no real bug. But the version field is useless without validation -- it gives false confidence that versioning is in place.\n\n**Fix:** Add version check in `isValidInbound`:\n```js\nfunction isValidInbound(e) {\n  return (\n    e.origin === SIDECAR_ORIGIN &&\n    e.data &&\n    typeof e.data === 'object' &&\n    e.data.sessionId === SESSION_ID &&\n    e.data.version === MSG_VERSION\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### M5. Portal detection via `isFiberAncestor` has false negatives with React Fragments and Suspense\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` lines 100-106\n\n**Problem:** The fiber.return walk checks `current.stateNode === ancestorElement`. But several fiber types have `stateNode === null`:\n- **Fragment** (`<>...</>`): tag 7, stateNode is null\n- **Suspense boundary**: tag 13, stateNode is a `SuspenseState` object (not a DOM element)\n- **Context.Provider**: tag 10, stateNode is null\n- **Mode** (StrictMode): tag 8, stateNode is null\n- **Profiler**: tag 12, stateNode is null\n\nIf the ancestor's `data-testid` is on a DOM element that corresponds to a fiber whose parent is a Fragment, the walk works fine (the Fragment's stateNode is null, so it's skipped, and the walk continues up). The issue arises when the `ancestorElement` is itself reached through a fiber with `stateNode === null` in between -- this doesn't cause problems because we're comparing against `ancestorElement` which is a DOM element with a HostComponent fiber.\n\nThe real false negative: **Error Boundaries**. When an error boundary catches and renders fallback UI, the fallback's fiber tree is a *new* child of the error boundary fiber. The original child's fiber tree is *detached*. If the `data-testid` ancestor was in the pre-error tree and the selected element is in the fallback tree, `isFiberAncestor` returns false (correct -- they are not in the same tree). But `element.closest('[data-testid]')` would still find the ancestor in the DOM because the DOM wasn't unmounted by the error boundary (only the fiber tree changed). This is a real false negative: the portal detection discards a valid testId.\n\n**Impact:** Edge case. Only triggers when an error boundary renders fallback UI that contains the selected element, and the testId is on a DOM ancestor outside the error boundary's scope. Low probability in practice.\n\n**Fix:** Document this as a known limitation. For Phase 4, consider checking `document.contains(testIdEl)` and `element.compareDocumentPosition(testIdEl)` as a secondary check when fiber ancestry fails.\n\n---\n\n## LOW\n\n### L1. `resolveSource` calls `getBoundingClientRect()` on every invocation -- including hover\n\n**File:** `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` lines 152-154, called from `handleHover` at line 344\n\n**Problem:** `handleHover` calls `resolveSource(target)` on every `mouseover` event. Inside `resolveSource`, `getBoundingClientRect()` is called. But `handleHover` also calls `target.getBoundingClientRect()` directly (line 340). So every hover triggers two `getBoundingClientRect()` calls on the same element.\n\n**Impact:** Minor performance waste. `getBoundingClientRect()` forces a layout reflow if the layout is dirty. Two calls in quick succession will usually get cached