ode's double-render in development only affects component render functions and effects -- it does not affect the fiber tree structure visible to external code reading `__reactFiber$` keys. The fiber tree after double-render is identical to after single-render. Concurrent features (`useTransition`, `startTransition`) similarly don't affect the committed fiber tree -- they only affect the *timing* of when the tree is committed. Since the inspector reads fibers on user events (click, hover), which happen after React has committed, concurrent features are not a concern.\n\nHydration mismatches could temporarily cause fiber keys to be absent (before hydration completes) or to point to different fibers (during hydration when server and client trees differ). The `isServerComponent: true` fallback handles this gracefully -- if no fiber is found, the element is treated as server-rendered.\n\n---\n\n## Summary: What Phases 4a/4b/5/6 Will Discover Is Missing\n\n1. **Element staleness (H1)**: `elementMap` entries go stale after React re-renders. Phase 4a's override engine will apply CSS to detached nodes.\n\n2. **Insufficient selection data (H2)**: No CSS custom property resolution, no `data-cortex-id`, no parent context. Phase 4a/4b need either a richer payload or a request/response message channel.\n\n3. **No message dispatch extensibility (H3)**: Every phase adds message types; the current if/else pattern doesn't scale.\n\n4. **No message protocol tests (H4)**: The boundary between inspector and panel is untested. Phase 4b's panel development will likely break the protocol without knowing it.\n\n5. **`isServerComponent` naming (M1)**: Phase 4b's panel will show misleading \"Server Component\" labels for non-React elements.\n\n6. **Template variable injection (M3)**: Phase 4b developers adding panel-to-inspector communication will need to understand the dual-mode authoring constraints, which are not documented.\n\nThe fiber traversal strategy (C2) is more correct than it appears at first glance -- the `in` check with fallback to Strategy B handles production builds and React 19 correctly, even though the comments don't explain this. The portal detection (C1, M5) is solid for the common case but has documented edge cases around error boundaries. The overall architecture -- pure functions exportable for testing, browser IIFE for runtime, postMessage bridge for cross-frame communication -- is sound and will serve downstream phases well once the extensibility and payload completeness issues are addressed.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>51363</total_tokens><tool_uses>17</tool_uses><duration_ms>191433</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-derricklee-cortex/tasks/a63796fc31b6948a9.output",
