          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a7c99f414815e77eb</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01GjqcxAbDcBwAopLBzF44RV</tool-use-id>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Frontend DevTools review\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Let me compile the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Deep Technical Review: `inspector.js`\n\n**Files under review:**\n- `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.js` (509 lines)\n- `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/client/inspector.d.ts` (59 lines)\n- `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/tests/client/inspector.test.ts` (522 lines)\n\n**Supporting context:**\n- `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/server.ts` (template variable replacement, injection)\n- `/Users/derricklee/cortex/visual-editor/src/inject.ts` (injection point)\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL FINDINGS\n\n### C1. Template Variable Replacement is an Injection Vector (Lines 17-18 of inspector.js, Lines 179-182 of server.ts)\n\n```js\nvar SESSION_ID = '{{SESSION_ID}}';\nvar SIDECAR_ORIGIN = '{{SIDECAR_ORIGIN}}';\n```\n\nThe server replaces these with simple `.replace()`:\n\n```ts\ncontent = content\n  .replace(/__SESSION_ID__/g, sessionId)\n  .replace(/__SIDECAR_ORIGIN__/g, `http://${host}:${port}`);\n```\n\nThere are two problems here. First, the template placeholders in the JS file use `{{SESSION_ID}}` and `{{SIDECAR_ORIGIN}}`, but the server replaces `__SESSION_ID__` and `__SIDECAR_ORIGIN__`. **These do not match.** The replacement never fires. This means `SESSION_ID` is the literal string `'{{SESSION_ID}}'` and `SIDECAR_ORIGIN` is `'{{SIDECAR_ORIGIN}}'` at runtime. Every `postToParent()` call targets a bogus origin. Every `isValidInbound()` check compares against the wrong origin. The entire postMessage bridge is non-functional.\n\nSecond, even if the placeholders were aligned, string interpolation into a JS string literal without escaping is dangerous. If `host` ever contains a single quote (unlikely for localhost, but the `host` option is user-supplied in `ServerOptions`), it would break the script or allow injection.\n\n**Impact:** The panel-to-inspector communication channel is completely broken. Select mode toggling via postMessage will never work. The inspector is essentially standalone with no cross-frame coordination.\n\n**Fix:** Align the placeholder tokens (`{{SESSION_ID}}` -> `__SESSION_ID__`, etc.), or change the server-side regex to match `{{...}}`. Add JSON-safe escaping for the replacement values. Consider using `JSON.stringify()` on the replacement value to handle edge cases.\n\n---\n\n### C2. `elementMap` Grows Unboundedly -- Memory Leak (Lines 286, 388)\n\n```js\nvar elementMap = {};\n// ...\nselectionId++;\nelementMap[selectionId] = target;\n```\n\nEvery click in select mode adds a DOM element reference to `elementMap` keyed by a monotonically increasing integer. This map is never pruned. It holds strong references to DOM elements, preventing garbage collection even after those elements are removed from the DOM (e.g., after React reconciliation, route changes, or HMR). Over a long editing session with many selections, this will accumulate arbitrarily many detached DOM nodes.\n\n**Impact:** Memory leak proportional to number of selections. In a long editing session, this could consume hundreds of megabytes if users are selecting elements on large pages with complex subtrees.\n\n**Fix:** Use a `WeakRef` wrapper or a bounded LRU with explicit size cap (e.g., last 50 selections). Alternatively, store only the most recent selection since the map is only used to apply CSS overrides to a previously selected element. A `Map` with explicit eviction on new selection would also work.\n\n---\n\n### C3. `handleHover` Calls `resolveSource` on Every Mouseover -- No Throttling (Lines 329-354)\n\n```js\nfunction handleHover(e) {\n  if (!active) return;\n  var target = e.target;\n  // ...\n  var info = resolveSource(target);\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n`mouseover`