erties. React attaches fiber keys as own properties, so this works today, but it is an implementation detail that has changed before (React 15 used `__reactInternalInstance$`, React 16+ uses `__reactFiber$` and `__reactInternalInstance$`).\n2. The function is called on every `resolveSource` invocation without caching. DOM elements can have many properties (data attributes, event handler properties, polyfill properties). The full key enumeration is O(n) in total properties.\n3. The prefix `__reactFiber$` misses `__reactInternalInstance$` which is what React 16 uses (and is still present in React 17). The code claims to support React 16-19 but only searches for the React 17+ key format.\n\n**Impact:** Silent failure on React 16 apps. Performance drag on every hover/click.\n\n**Fix:** Also check for `__reactInternalInstance$` prefix. Cache fiber keys per element instance using a `WeakMap<Element, string[]>`. Consider using `Object.getOwnPropertyNames()` if any frameworks set non-enumerable fiber keys.\n\n---\n\n### H2. `walkComponentChain` Strategy A/B Detection Has a Version-Boundary Bug (Lines 49-81)\n\n```js\nif ('_debugOwner' in fiber) {\n  // Strategy A: React 18\n  // ...\n}\n// Strategy B: React 19\n```\n\nThe `'_debugOwner' in fiber` check is correct for distinguishing React 18 from 19, but it breaks for:\n1. **React 17:** Fibers have `_debugOwner` but the owner chain semantics differ from React 18 (less reliable in concurrent mode).\n2. **React 19 canary/RC builds:** Some React 19 canaries still had `_debugOwner` before it was removed. The `in` check would incorrectly route to Strategy A.\n3. **Mixed React versions:** Micro-frontends or module federation setups can have multiple React instances. Different fibers on the same page could need different strategies.\n\nMore critically, Strategy B's tag filtering is incomplete:\n\n```js\nif (currentB.tag === 0 || currentB.tag === 1) {\n```\n\nThis only matches FunctionComponent (0) and ClassComponent (1). It misses:\n- `ForwardRef` (tag 11) -- extremely common with React.forwardRef\n- `MemoComponent` (tag 14) -- React.memo wrappers\n- `SimpleMemoComponent` (tag 15)\n- `LazyComponent` (tag 16)\n\nThese are all user-authored components that would be useful in the chain. Missing `ForwardRef` specifically means that any component wrapped in `React.forwardRef()` (very common in design systems like Mantine, MUI, Radix) will be invisible in the component chain.\n\n**Impact:** Component chains on React 19 will be sparse and missing most design system components. This undermines the entire source resolution strategy since the component chain is the primary signal for `classifyElement`.\n\n**Fix:** Expand the tag set: `[0, 1, 11, 14, 15, 16].indexOf(currentB.tag) !== -1`. Consider a Set for O(1) lookup. Add a test for ForwardRef fibers.\n\n---\n\n### H3. `isServerComponent` Detection is a False Inference (Lines 114, 134-137)\n\n```js\nvar isServerComponent = true;\n\n// Strategy 2: React fiber chain\nvar fiber = null;\n// ...\nif (fiber) {\n  isServerComponent = false;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nThe logic says: \"if there's no React fiber on this DOM element, it must be a server component.\" This is wrong for multiple scenarios:\n1. **Non-React elements:** Static HTML, SVG, or elements rendered by other libraries (D3, a charting library, an embedded widget) will have no fiber but are not server components.\n2. **React host portals to non-React containers:** The portal target has no fiber.\n3. **Elements inside `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`:** These are raw DOM, no fibers.\n4. **Server-rendered HTML before hydration:** During the hydration window, many elements have no fiber yet. They are client components that haven't hydrated.\n\n**Impact:** Misleading `isServerComponent: true` flag sent to the panel. If the panel uses this to determine editing constraints (e.g., \"can't edit server components\"), it would incorrectly lock out editable elements.\n\n**Fix:** Rename to `hasClientFiber: boolean` (describes what was actually detected, not what it means). Or implement a more nuanced heuristic: check for `data-rsc` attributes, React streaming markers (`<!--$-->`, `<!--/$-->`), or the absence of any React root on the page.\n\n---\n\n### H4. Selector/Targeting Strategy is Missing -- CSS Override Survival Unclear (Lines 388-401)\n\nThe `handleClick` function captures `selectionId`, `info`, and `computed` styles, but there is no CSS selector generation anywhere in this file. The `elementMap[selectionId] = target` stores a direct DOM reference, which means:\n\n1. **HMR:** When Vite or webpack HMR replaces a module, React unmounts and remounts the affected subtree. The stored DOM reference becomes a detached node. There is no re-acquisition strategy.\n2. **React reconciliation:** A state change can cause React to create a new DOM element for the same logical component. The stored reference goes stale.\n3. **Route changes:** SPA navigation destroys and recreates large portions of the DOM.\n\nThe code stores raw element references but provides no mechanism to re-resolve them after DOM mutations. There is also no `MutationObserver` to detect when a selected element is removed.\n\n**Impact:** After any DOM mutation affecting the selected element, the panel's selection is silently stale. CSS overrides applied via `elementMap` references would target detached nodes and have no visible effect.\n\n**Fix:** Generate a stable CSS selector (data-testid path, component chain fingerprint, or nth-child path) at selection time. Store both the selector and the DOM reference. Use a `MutationObserver` to detect removal and re-resolve via the selector. Alternatively, use a `data-zerofog-selected` attribute stamped on the element, which survives React reconciliation if the element identity is preserved.\n\n---\n\n### H5. `postMessage` Origin Validation Accepts Exact Match Only -- No Protocol-Relative Handling (Lines 263-270)\n\n```js\nfunction isValidInbound(e) {\n  return (\n    e.origin === SIDECAR_ORIGIN &&\n    e.data &&\n    typeof e.data === 'object' &&\n    e.data.sessionId === SESSION_ID\n  );\n}\n```\n\n`SIDECAR_ORIGIN` is `http://localhost:3100` (from server.ts line 182). But:\n1. If the browser upgrades to HTTPS (via HSTS, service worker, or browser extension), the origin becomes `https://localhost:3100` and the check fails.\n2. If the user accesses via `127.0.0.1` instead of `localhost`, origin mismatch.\n3. If IPv6 `[::1]` is used, origin mismatch.\n\nCombined with C1 (template variables not replaced), this is currently always failing, but even if fixed, the exact-match strategy is brittle for localhost development.\n\n**Impact:** postMessage bridge silently broken in many common localhost access patterns.\n\n**Fix:** Parse both origins as URLs and compare hostname/port, normalizing localhost variants. Or, since this is a dev-only tool, validate that the origin is any loopback address on the expected port.\n\n---\n\n### H6. Event Listener Capture Phase + `stopPropagation` Breaks Application Event Handlers (Lines 357-365, 362-375)\n\n```js\ndocument.addEventListener('pointerdown', handlePointerDown, true);\ndocument.addEventListener('click', handleClick, true);\n```\n\nAnd in the handlers:\n\n```js\nfunction handlePointerDown(e) {\n  if (!active || !selectMode) return;\n  e.stopPropagation();\n  e.preventDefault();\n}\n\nfunction handleClick(e) {\n  if (!active || !selectMode) return;\n  e.stopPropagation();\n  e.preventDefault();\n}\n```\n\nUsing capture phase + `stopPropagation` means:\n1. **Every click and pointerdown** in the entire page is intercepted during select mode. This prevents dropdown menus from opening, form submissions, link navigations, drag-and-drop, and all other pointer interactions.\n2. `preventDefault` on pointerdown suppresses focus, text selection, and native drag behaviors.\n3. The app under inspection becomes completely non-interactive during select mode. This is likely intentional but has an edge case: if the user needs to interact with the app to reach a specific UI state before selecting, they must exit select mode first, perform the interaction, then re-enter select mode. This UX limitation should be documented.\n\nMore critically, `stopPropagation` in capture phase prevents the event from reaching any other capture-phase listeners on the document, including analytics libraries (Segment, Amplitude), error monitoring (Sentry click breadcrumbs), and accessibility tools.\n\n**Impact:** Select mode silently breaks analytics, error tracking, and accessibility tooling. Users may not notice these silent failures during development.\n\n**Fix:** Use `stopImmediatePropagation` only if you truly need to block all other listeners (current behavior is already close). But more importantly, consider whether `stopPropagation` is needed at all -- `preventDefault` alone is sufficient to prevent default browser behavior. The application's React event handlers are on the bubble phase and won't fire if the event never reaches them, but React 17+ attaches listeners to the root container, not the document, so `stopPropagation` from a document-level capture listener will still block React's synthetic event system.\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM FINDINGS\n\n### M1. `classifyElement` Hardcodes Mantine Component Names (Lines 169-241)\n\nThe classification function is tightly coupled to the Mantine UI library:\n\n```js\nif (['AppShell', 'Navbar', 'Header', 'Footer', 'Aside'].indexOf(compName) !== -1)\n  return 'layout';\n```\n\nComponent names like `AppShell`, `ActionIcon`, `NavLink`, `SimpleGrid` are Mantine-specific. MUI equivalents (`AppBar`, `IconButton`, `DataGrid`), Chakra equivalents (`ChakraProvider`, `FormControl`), and Radix equivalents (`NavigationMenu`, `ToggleGroup`) would all fall through to `'unknown'`.\n\n**Impact:** Classification accuracy drops significantly on non-Mantine codebases. The `elementType` field in selection payloads becomes mostly `'unknown'`.\n\n**Fix:** Make the classification rules configurable via a lookup table that the server injects alongside the template variables. Provide presets for common design systems (Mantine, MUI, Chakra, Radix, Ant Design). The tag-based fallback (lines 227-238) is framework-agnostic and should be weighted more heavily.\n\n---\n\n### M2. `closest()` Polyfill Absence (Lines 118-122, 339, 375)\n\n```js\nvar testIdEl = ownTestId\n  ? element\n  : element.closest\n    ? element.closest('[data-testid]')\n    : null;\n```\n\nThe `element.closest` guard is good defensive coding, but:\n1. `target.closest` on lines 339 and 375 inside the IIFE is called without the same guard:\n   ```js\n   if (target.closest && target.closest('[data-zerofog-ui=\"true\"]')) return;\n   ```\n   This is actually guarded, good. But the pattern is inconsistent with `resolveSource` which uses a ternary vs. the `&&` short-circuit.\n2. `closest()` is supported in all modern browsers (IE excluded), so this is fine for the target audience. But SVG elements in some browsers have limited `closest()` support. If the user hovers over an SVG `<path>` or `<circle>`, `closest()` may not exist on SVGElement in older WebKit.\n\n**Impact:** Potential crash on SVG elements in edge-case browsers.\n\n**Fix:** The existing guards are sufficient for modern browsers. If broader support is needed, add `Element.prototype.closest` polyfill or wrap all `closest` calls in a shared helper.\n\n---\n\n### M3. `textContent` Captures Entire Subtree Text (Line 151)\n\n```js\nvar text = (element.textContent || '').substring(0, 100);\n```\n\n`textContent` returns the concatenated text of all descendants. For a `<div>` containing a complex card component, this could be hundreds of characters of concatenated label text, prices, descriptions, etc. The 100-character truncation helps, but the captured text is still noisy and not useful for identification.\n\n**Impact:** The `text` field in selection payloads is unreliable for anything except leaf text nodes. If used for selector generation or element re-identification, it would produce false matches.\n\n**Fix:** Use `element.innerText` (respects visibility, closer to rendered text) or only capture `textContent` from leaf elements (those with no element children). Alternatively, capture `element.childNodes[0].nodeValue` for direct text nodes only.\n\n---\n\n### M4. No `mouseout`/`mouseleave` Handler -- Overlay Persists When Cursor Leaves Window (Lines 329-354)\n\nThe hover overlay is positioned on `mouseover` but never hidden on `mouseout`. If the cursor leaves the browser window, the overlay remains visible over the last hovered element. It only moves when the cursor re-enters and triggers a new `mouseover`.\n\n**Impact:** Visual glitch -- the blue hover overlay \"sticks\" to the last element when the cursor exits the viewport, which can confuse users into thinking an element is still being targeted.\n\n**Fix:** Add a `mouseout` handler on `document` that hides the overlay when `e.relatedTarget` is null (cursor left the window):\n\n```js\nfunction handleMouseOut(e) {\n  if (!active) return;\n  if (!e.relatedTarget) {\n    overlay.style.display = 'none';\n    labelEl.style.display = 'none';\n  }\n}\ndocument.addEventListener('mouseout', handleMouseOut, true);\n```\n\n---\n\n### M5. Overlay Positioning Uses Fixed Coordinates -- Breaks With Scroll (Lines 321-326)\n\n```js\nfunction positionOverlay(el, rect) {\n  el.style.top = rect.top + 'px';\n  el.style.left = rect.left + 'px';\n  el.style.width = rect.width + 'px';\n  el.style.height = rect.height + 'px';\n  el.style.display = 'block';\n}\n```\n\n`getBoundingClientRect()` returns viewport-relative coordinates, and the overlay uses `position:fixed`. This is correct for static pages. But:\n1. **CSS transforms on ancestors:** If a parent element has `transform: scale(0.5)`, `getBoundingClientRect()` returns the transformed bounds, but the overlay's `position:fixed` is relative to the viewport, not the transform context. The overlay will misalign.\n2. **`will-change: transform`:** Creates a new containing block for fixed positioning. If any ancestor of the target has this, the overlay's fixed positioning is relative to that ancestor, not the viewport.\n3. **Zoom/pinch:** Browser zoom changes the relationship between CSS pixels and viewport coordinates.\n\n**Impact:** Overlay misalignment on pages using CSS transforms, `will-change`, or browser zoom. This is common in animation-heavy UIs.\n\n**Fix:** Append the overlay to `document.documentElement` (not `body`) to avoid `body` margin/transform issues. For transform compensation, use `getComputedStyle` to walk up the ancestor chain checking for `transform` or `will-change` properties, or use the `IntersectionObserver` API to get untransformed bounds.\n\n---\n\n### M6. No Handling of Scroll During Selection (Line 378)\n\nWhen the user clicks to select, `getBoundingClientRect()` returns the element's current viewport-relative position. But the selected overlay (green) remains at those fixed coordinates even as the user scrolls. The selection highlight detaches from the actual element.\n\n**Impact:** Confusing visual state after scrolling. Users see the green selection box in the wrong position.\n\n**Fix:** Attach a passive `scroll` event listener that re-positions the selected overlay using the stored element reference's current `getBoundingClientRect()`. Use `requestAnimationFrame` to batch updates. Alternatively, use an absolutely-positioned overlay as a sibling of the target element instead of a fixed-positioned overlay.\n\n---\n\n### M7. `deactivate()` Called Inside `activate()` Creates Brief Deselected Event (Lines 463-465)\n\n```js\nfunction activate() {\n  // Idempotent — clean up before re-attaching\n  deactivate();\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n`deactivate()` dispatches `zerofog:deselected` and sends `postToParent('zerofog:deselected')` if `wasActive` is true (line 457). So re-activating while already active sends a deselected event immediately followed by a ready event. The panel would briefly see a deselection, potentially clearing UI state, before the ready event re-establishes the connection.\n\n**Impact:** Transient UI flicker in the panel during re-activation. Selection state is lost on re-activation.\n\n**Fix:** Add a `silent` parameter to `deactivate()` or check a flag to suppress the `deselected` event when called from `activate()`.\n\n---\n\n### M8. `handleMessage` Does Not Validate `msg.version` (Lines 430-439)\n\n```js\nfunction handleMessage(e) {\n  if (!isValidInbound(e)) return;\n  var msg = e.data;\n  if (msg.type === 'inspector:enter-select') {\n    // ...\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe outbound messages include `version: MSG_VERSION` (line 254) but inbound messages are not checked for version compatibility. If the panel and inspector are at different versions (e.g., cached inspector script), silently processing incompatible messages could cause subtle bugs.\n\n**Impact:** Version skew between panel and inspector could cause protocol-level bugs.\n\n**Fix:** Check `msg.version === MSG_VERSION` in `isValidInbound` or `handleMessage`.\n\n---\n\n## LOW FINDINGS\n\n### L1. ES5 Style in 2026 -- Maintenance Cost (Entire file)\n\nThe file uses `var`, manual `for` loops, `indexOf !== -1`, and `Array.prototype.slice.call()`. Comments note this is intentional for browser compatibility, but the script is served from a localhost dev server that only needs to run in the developer's own browser. Modern browsers universally support ES2020+.\n\n**Impact:** Higher maintenance burden. `let`/`const`, `for...of`, `Array.from()`, `includes()`, `Map`/`Set`, and arrow functions would make the code shorter and less error-prone.\n\n**Fix:** Target ES2020 in the tsup IIFE build config. Write modern JS and let the bundler downlevel if needed.\n\n---\n\n### L2. `classifyElement` Uses Linear Search with `indexOf` (Lines 169-241)\n\n```js\nif (['AppShell', 'Navbar', 'Header', 'Footer', 'Aside'].indexOf(compName) !== -1)\n```\n\nEach classification check creates a new array literal and scans it linearly. With 7 categories and ~40 total component names, this is O(n*m) per call where n = chain length and m = total component names.\n\n**Impact:** Negligible for current workload (only called on click), but would matter if called on hover.\n\n**Fix:** Pre-build `Set` objects or a `Map<string, ElementCategory>` at module load time.\n\n---\n\n### L3. `data-zerofog-ui` Guard Does Not Cover Overlay Children (Lines 339, 375)\n\n```js\nif (target.closest && target.closest('[data-zerofog-ui=\"true\"]')) return;\n```\n\nThe overlays and label have no children, so `closest` checking the target itself is sufficient. But if the label or overlay ever gains child elements (e.g., a close button, a tooltip), clicks on those children would be handled correctly by `closest` walking up. This is future-proof. No issue currently, just noting the pattern is correct.\n\n---\n\n### L4. `getBoundingClientRect` Fallback Object (Line 152-154)\n\n```js\nvar bounds = element.getBoundingClientRect\n  ? element.getBoundingClientRect()\n  : { top: 0, left: 0, width: 0, height: 0 };\n```\n\nThe fallback returns an incomplete `DOMRect` (missing `right`, `bottom`, `x`, `y`). If consumers expect the full `DOMRect` interface, they'll get `undefined` for the missing fields.\n\n**Impact:** Downstream code using `bounds.right` or `bounds.bottom` would get undefined. The type definition in `inspector.d.ts` only declares `top/left/width/height`, which is consistent, so this is only a problem if the types diverge.\n\n**Fix:** Complete the fallback: `{ top: 0, left: 0, width: 0, height: 0, right: 0, bottom: 0, x: 0, y: 0 }`.\n\n---\n\n### L5. Test Coverage Gaps\n\nThe test suite is solid for the pure functions but has notable gaps:\n1. **No test for `findReactFiberKeys` with `__reactInternalInstance$`** -- only tests `__reactFiber$`.\n2. **No test for `walkComponentChain` with ForwardRef/Memo fiber tags** -- only tests tags 0, 1, and 5.\n3. **No 